<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: SPD's Rau Elected German President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 23 (Xinhua)--German Social Democrat (SPD) Johannes
Rau was elected as the country's eighth president by Sunday's
parliamentary session in the historic building of Reichstag in
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Rau won the election at the second round ballot at which 690
lawmakers voted in favor. He had failed to gain the necessary 670
votes at first round.
</P>
<P>
Other two candidates, both women, were Dagmar Schipanski of
Germany's largest opposition, the conservative Christian
Democratic Union (CDU), and Uta Ranke-Heinemann of the left wing
Democratic Socialist Party (PDS).
</P>
<P>
Schipanski, a physician, had won 588 from 1333 valid votes in
the first round, while Ranke-Heinemann won 69, and Rau, 657. But
in the second round, some legislators voted in favor Rau.
</P>
<P>
Knowing his victory, Rau declared he would serve not only the
Germans, but also millions of foreigners living in Germany.
</P>
<P>
" I am president of all Germans but also the partner for
dialogue of all people living here without German passport," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Rau stressed the Germans must keep good relationship both with
the 7.3 million foreigners and with all neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
" I will never be a nationalist but rather a patriot," said
Rau, adding, " a patriot is someone who loves his motherland. A
nationalist is someone who despises others' motherlands."
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Kosovo conflict, he said, "we are living in the
war time, and I wish this war will not last long." Rau announced
his support to NATO's air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
One of the first foreign state heads that congratulated Rau's
election was French President Jacques Chirac, who said he was
expecting to cooperate with Rau to promote the two countries'
friendship.
</P>
<P>
And his party boss and German Chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, said
Rau's election will bring Germans with great hopes, especially
those living in east Germany.
</P>
<P>
Rau, a moderate SPD politician and former Premier of the North
Rhine-Westphalia State who had been ruling for 20 years, will on
July 1 formally succeed the outgoing President Roman Herzog.
</P>
<P>
In Germany's political life, federal presidency is largely a
ceremonial role with most power be concentrated in the
chancellory.
</P>
<P>
But the prestige post does provide Rau with a key platform for
authority, since he is given the power to appoint chancellor and
veto legislations.
</P>
<P>
Rau, popular inside the party because of his ability to draw
opposing sides together, is well known as a joke-teller, a keen
christian and a Bible quote.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's election in Berlin, in which 669 lawmakers from the
lower chamber of Germany's parliament, Budestag, and the same
number of delegates from the country's 16 states took part,
coincided with the 50 th anniversary of Germany's Basic Law, the
country's constitution since 1949.
</P>
<P>
And Parliamentary president Wolfgang Thierse, who presided over
the assembly, depicted it as " the first election for a president
residing in Berlin." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
