<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Hails Positive Results of Khatami's Arab Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, May 23 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) has hailed the
positive results of Iranian President Mohammed Khatami's latest
visits to three Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on Sunday, Arab League Secretary General
Esmat Abdel-Meguid said the league was following the positive
results of Khatami's visits to Syria, Saudi Arabia and Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The league viewed the visit as a confidence-building step,
which would lead to solid Arab-Iranian relations and serve mutual
interests, Abdel-Meguid said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami visited Syria, Saudi Arabia and Qatar on May 13-20 in a
bid to seek further promotion of relations or improved ties with
the three countries.
</P>
<P>
Damascus has been Tehran's long-time ally in the Arab world. It
supported Tehran during 1980-88 Iran-Iraq war.
</P>
<P>
But ties between Iran and Gulf Arab countries, including Qatar
and Saudi Arabia have been tense for two decades due to Iran's
1979 Islamic Revolution, which Arab countries viewed as a threat.
And during the Iran-Iraq war, the Gulf nations sided with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iran's general relations with the Arab world have been eased
since Khatami took office in 1997. Khatami, a political moderate,
has repeated Tehran's readiness to end hostility and establish
mutual trust with Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid expressed hope that the Iranian authorities will
reflect on pending problems between Iran and Arab countries,
especially its territorial disputes with the United Arab Emirates
(UAE).
</P>
<P>
He called on Iran to respond to the stand of the Emirates and
the repeated Arab call to settle the dispute over three Gulf
islands peacefully in accordance with the international law.
</P>
<P>
Both Iran and the UAE have claimed sovereignty over the islands
of Greater Tunb, Lesser Tunb and Abu Musa near the strategic
Strait of Hormuz.
</P>
<P>
But the two countries have voiced willingness to solve the
problem through peaceful means. The UAE has proposed the disputes
be submitted to international arbitration while Iran prefers
bilateral talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
