<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President Calls for Financial Support for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
said here Sunday that his diplomatic shuttles to mediate a
peaceful solution to the nine-month war in the Democratic Republic
of Congo (DRC) has been costly and he will appreciate any
financial assistance for the peace mission.
</P>
<P>
Before leaving for Kenyan capital Nairobi to attend the 4th
summit of the Common Market for the Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA) scheduled for Monday and Tuesday, Chiluba said that his
government has accumulated huge cost in travel expenses and other
activities related to the peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
The president, who was mandated one year ago by the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) to mediate a peaceful
settlement of the conflict in the DRC, expressed his appreciation
for the gesture of the European Union to off-set some of the
expenses.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, Chiluba shuttled frequently among the
countries concerned for an early end to the war in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
On the COMESA, the Zambian president said that COMESA member
states are moving very fast toward achieving a free trade area and
regional economic integration.
</P>
<P>
As the current chairman of the COMESA, Chiluba said that a
number of members have reduced their tariffs by 80 percent in a
bid to achieve zero tariffs by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Southern Africa will only achieve a meaningful economic growth
when a single bloc is integrated, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He also urged COMESA members to speed up their efforts to
strengthen their individual economies.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba said the large economies like South Africa can create
more wealth in their partnership with the small ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
