<HEADLINE> Iranian President Discusses Bilateral Ties With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
on Sunday discussed bilateral relations and regional developments
with Bahraini Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin Isa al-Khalifa in a telephone
conversation.
</P>
<P>
Khatami expressed satisfaction with the new atmosphere
prevailing between the two countries and called for expansion of
these ties, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that the cordial relations between
the two nations would lead to the preservation of security in the
region.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian president also underlined that the destiny of the
regional countries is interdependent. These countries can help
each other and cooperate in the future, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Bahraini emir termed the relations between Iran and
regional countries including Bahrain as very good.
</P>
<P>
Extending invitation to Khatami to visit Bahrain, Sheikh Hamad
said that the exchange of official visits is important in
expansion of bilateral ties and resolving outstanding issues
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Bahrain exchanged their ambassadors recently, some 30
months after the two countries downgraded their diplomatic ties
over an alleged pro-Iranian attempt to overthrow the Bahraini
government by force. Iran denied the charges.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharazi visited Manama in
March, following the death of the former emir, Sheikh Isa Bin
Salman al-Khalifa, to convey Tehran's condolences.
</P>
<P>
Bahraini Foreign Minister Sheikh Mohammad bin Mubarak
al-Khalifa paid his two-day landmark visit to Tehran earlier this
month.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and its Gulf Arab neighbors have
improved after President Khatami came to power in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
Khatami visited Saudi Arabia and Qatar last week, the first
by an Iranian president since the Islamic revolution in
1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
