<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000 GMT, May 23 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Dozens of angry Palestinians clashed on Sunday
with Israeli soldiers in Der Qades Village near the West Bank city
of Ramallah, the Voice of Palestine (VOP) said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians were protesting against Israel's confiscation
of their land, which were used for building a road, VOP added.
</P>
<P>
The clash erupted when several Israeli bulldozers started to
pave the land, and the angry Palestinians tried to stop them. No
casualties were reported so far. (BC-Israel-Clash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Speaker of the Egyptian People's Assembly (Parliament)
Ahmed Fathi Sorour has strongly condemned the NATO's missile
attack on the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Sorour made the condemnation in a meeting on Saturday with Li
Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of the Chinese
People's Political Consultative Conference.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Li, who arrived here on Friday for a
six-day official visit, reiterated the Chinese government's solemn
and just stand on the U.S.-led NATO's attack on the Chinese
Embassy. (BC-Egypt-China-NATO Attack)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A visiting Chinese leader underlined on Sunday that
seeking common ground while reserving differences, and equality
and mutual benefit form the basic principles of the contemporary
international relations.
</P>
<P>
"China sincerely hopes to co-exist peacefully and develop
jointly with all the other countries on the basis of the
principle," said Li Ruihuan, chairman of the National Committee of
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference.
</P>
<P>
Li, who arrived here on Friday for a six-day official visit,
made the remarks during his meeting with Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak in the day.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said the Chinese people are "sincere friends of the
Egyptian people."
</P>
<P>
He termed the Egyptian-Chinese relations as good, saying the
leaders of the two countries always exchange visits in an effort
to further promote the cooperation ties. (BC-Egypt-China-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli prime minister-elect Ehud Barak spelt out
the strategy for coalition talks Sunday, beginning his drive to
build a broad-based government with an aim of healing internal
rift and achieving national consensus on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
His aides will begin talks first with parties that supported
him or remained neutral during the elections, and only afterwards
with other parties, according to the strategy laid down by Barak
during a meeting with his coalition negotiation team.
</P>
<P>
After the first round of talks with all the potential
coalition partners, Barak will publicize the guiding principles of
his government and invite those parties agreeing to the
principles to join the government, said David Liba'i, former
justice minister and head of the negotiation team.
(BC-Israel-Barak)


