<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Chairman Urges Africans to Display Collective </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Current chairman of the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) and President of Burkina Faso,
Blaise Compaore has urged all Africans to display a collective
surge of energy.
</P>
<P>
In his message to African people issued here Sunday to mark the
36th anniversary of the African Liberation Day which falls on May
25, President Compaore said that the establishment of the OAU on
May 25, 1963 "wrote one of the most beautiful pages" in the
African history.
</P>
<P>
"Once independence was recovered, the dream consisted in
leaving the Africans alone with the exhilarating but noble
responsibility and heavy duty to change, with their own hands and
intelligency, Africa into a haven of peace, justice, solidarity,
prosperity and brotherhood," said Compaore
</P>
<P>
However, he said, "more than thirty years have elapsed since,
and the dream is yet to fulfill."
</P>
<P>
The OAU chairman pointed out that Africa's independence remains
very fragile in a world where those who have the military and
economic might lay down the law and rule over humanity.
</P>
<P>
"Africa is at the crossroads", he noted, adding that "all over
the continent unbridled crises, tensions and wars are erupting and
coming in the foreground in virtually all our states."
</P>
<P>
"At the dawn of the third millenium, I would therefore like to
fervently wish for a greater mobilization in Africa," he said.
</P>
<P>
"An Africa where justice, peace, development, democracy,
solidarity and prosperity, will no longer be concepts, but
palpable realities deeply rooted in our societies", he expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
