<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-23 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Starts Formation of Coalition Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Israeli prime minister-elect Ehud
Barak spelt out the strategy for coalition talks Sunday, beginning
his drive to build a broad-based government with an aim of healing
internal rift and achieving national consensus on the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
His aides will begin talks first with parties that supported
him or remained neutral during the elections, and only afterwards
with other parties, according to the strategy laid down by Barak
during a meeting with his coalition negotiation team.
</P>
<P>
After the first round of talks with all the potential
coalition partners, Barak will publicize the guiding principles of
his government and invite those parties agreeing to the
principles to join the government, said David Liba'i, former
justice minister and head of the negotiation team.
</P>
<P>
Barak will have 45 days to form a coalition after the Central
Election Committee officially publicize the election results
Tuesday. His aides said he is in no rush to wrap up the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Unlike outgoing Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, who found it
difficult to cobble together even a narrow coalition after he
won the 1996 elections, Barak enjoys a luxury of riches: he has
several coalition models to choose after left and center parties
won a majority in the Knesset (parliament) elections.
</P>
<P>
But Barak has pledged after his landslide victory last Monday
that he will establish a coalition as broad-based as possible to
achieve national unity and a consensus in order to take tough
decisions on peace talks with the Palestinians and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Sources in his One Israel alliance have said that Barak is
seeking a coalition with at least 75 seats in the Knesset, backed
by another 10 from three Arab parties.
</P>
<P>
This indicated that the former army chief might include the
right-wing Likud party or the ultra-religious party Shas, or both
of them, in his coalition.
</P>
<P>
The Likud, a traditional counterbalance to the Labor in the
Knesset, suffered a crushing defeat in the elections, lost 13
seats from 32 in the outgoing Knesset.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shas, a party of Middle East Jews, scored a
stunning victory, capturing 17 seats in the 120-member Knesset,
up from 10 last time and securing its position as the third
largest party after One Israel and the Likud.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon, acting as temporary leader of
Likud after Netanyahu resigned his leadership following the
elections, convened Sunday Likud members in the next Knesset to
discuss the party's position in the coalition talks.
</P>
<P>
A majority of the party members, including Sharon himself,
agreed that the Likud should not reject a possible offer by Barak
to join a coalition. But Sharon asked the Likud members not to
express themselves publicly on this issue.
</P>
<P>
Sharon denied reports that he has been attempting to create a
right-wing bloc with other right-wing parties in the Knesset in
order to strengthen their positions in the coalition talks.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu, who did not attend the meeting, is expected to
announce his resignation from the Knesset later this week.
</P>
<P>
In a sign of strong opposition to a possible inclusion of Shas
in the next government, Israel Radio reported that Barak's office
was flooded Sunday with more than 20,000 e-mails which asked him
to exclude Shas out of any coalition he forms.
</P>
<P>
A maker and breaker of coalition governments for years, Shas
has been in the frontline in a heating-up cultural battle between
the religious and the secular.
</P>
<P>
Its spectacular showing in the elections was widely seen as a
powerful support by low-income Israelis for the party's leader,
Aryeh Deri, who was sentenced to four years in jail last month
for corruption and fraud.
</P>
<P>
The left-wing party Meretz, a natural coalition partner of One
Israel, and Shinui, a new secular party that won six seats on a
platform against ultra-Orthodox control of public life, have said
that they would not sit in any coalition with Shas so long as
Deri could call the shots.
</P>
<P>
In a move seen as an attempt to boost Shas' chances of
entering Barak's coalition, Deri announced his resignation from
parliament one day after the elections, but said he would stay on
as chairman of the party.
</P>
<P>
In response, Barak said that he will not deal with Shas so
long as Deri could still control the party from behind the scene.
</P>
<P>
Some of his senior aides, however, said that Deri's move has
cleared the way for Shas to enter the coalition talks.
</P>
<P>
"While the party (One Israel) must be aware of the feeling of
its anti-Shas supporters, it must deal with the issue of unity,"
said Shlomo Ben-Ami, a senior Labor Knesset member.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Barak might bring Shas into his coalition
on condition that Deri totally resigns from its leadership and
the party agrees to put its educational and welfare networks
under the control of the government.
</P>
<P>
But Barak has kept his cards close to his chest. Before his
meeting with President Ezer Weizman Sunday, the first since the
elections, he was asked by reporters if he would include Shas in
his government, but he walked away with the president without
giving an answer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
