<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Iraqis Injured in U.S. Air Raids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Two Iraqi people were injured
on Sunday in U.S. and British warplanes attacks on civilian
facilities in northern Iraq, an Iraqi military spokesman
announced.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that at 10:30 (0630 GMT), 12 formations
of enemy warplanes coming from Turkish airspace violated northern
Iraqi airspace over Dohuk, Neineva and Erbil provinces.
</P>
<P>
The enemy formations attacked civilian facilities and some
military sites in this region, injuring two civilians, said the
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi anti-aircraft units fired back and forced the enemy
planes to flee at 13:35 (0935 GMT), he added.
</P>
<P>
Enemy warplanes also violated southern Iraqi airspace at
10:10 (0610 GMT) and 17:00 (1300 GMT) when 34 formations
coming from Saudi and Kuwaiti bases flew over Basra, Thi-Qar,
Muthana and Misan provinces, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Since the U.S. and Britain launched four nights of airstrikes
against Iraq last December, their warplanes have been regularly
attacking Iraqi military and civilian targets, causing severe
civilian casualties and property damages.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led western allies imposed the no-fly zones in
Iraq following the 1991 Gulf War with a claimed aim of
protecting the Kurds in the north and the Shiite Muslims in
the south from "Baghdad's suppression."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has declared that it does not recognize these
restricted zones and vowed to continue confronting any allied
plane violating its airspace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
