<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angola Deregulates Foreign Exchange Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Angola has abandoned its 25-year old
fixed exchange rate system and adopt a free floating exchange
rate, which will take effect from Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Aguinaldo Jaime, governor of the Angolan National Bank, the
central bank of the country, said Saturday night the government
gave up the fixed rate because it has almost run out of foreign
exchange reserve and was no longer able to maintain the fixed
rate.
</P>
<P>
The governor said the central bank will deregulate the foreign
exchange rate and the rate will be determined by the market alone.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, the official exchange rate was 710,000 Kwanza to
one U.S. dollar while at the black market one dollar could buy two
million Kwanza.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, most of Angola's foreign exchange and local currency
had gone to the black market.
</P>
<P>
Jaime noted that the in the medium and long run, the country's
economy will "benefit from the floating rate," because banks can
buy the urgently-needed foreign exchanges and encourage savings in
local currency Kwanza.
</P>
<P>
More importantly, the governor said, the banks will hence be
able to finance the development projects in the war-torn southern
African country.
</P>
<P>
Angola had adopted fixed exchange rate system ever since it won
 independence in 1975.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged civil war has made the Angolan government's
military spending soaring up. while the low prices in the
international crude oil market has made its major foreign exchange
income decreased by one third.
</P>
<P>
At the end of last year, Angola fell in the most serious
financial crisis in its history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
