<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile:Johannes Rau, from Apprentice to German President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 23 (Xinhua)--Never completing his high school
education and beginning his career as an apprentice with a
publishing house, Social Democrat (SPD) Johannes Rau was elected
as Germany's eighth Federal President Sunday in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Rau, 68, had been governing Germany's largest state, North
Rhine-Westphalia, for 20 years as State Premier before he resigned
last year and then entered national political stage.
</P>
<P>
Born in the industrial city of Wuppertal, west Germany, and the
son of a pastor, Rau had worked 14 years (1954-1967) for a
theological publishing company. Then, since 1958, he began his
career as an SPD politician, and was elected as leader of the
city's SPD youth movement.
</P>
<P>
During 1964 to 1967 Rau served as Wuppertal's SPD party chief,
and two years later he was elected as the city mayor, his first
major post. Nine years after entering SPD's national executive
circle in 1968, Rau became the party's state leader.
</P>
<P>
Rau, coming from SPD's more moderate wing and a well known
joke-teller, has a nickname of "Brother Johannes" because he
quotes the Bible for every occasion.
</P>
<P>
He owns the ability to draw opposing sides together and to
defuse conflict, Rau's party friends said.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledged as a pro-business leader, Rau has linked his name
with a set of structure reforms to help Nord Rhine-Westphalia's
declining mining and coal sectors after he elected as the state's
premier in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Rau sticks to SPD's ideal of solidarity with weaker members of
society, but this belief is linked to a firm insistence on
pragmatic solutions but not utopian illusions, said one of
Germany's most influential newspapers, Frankfurter Allgeimeine.
</P>
<P>
Before taking part in the presidential election, Rau had twice
contended for posts as national leader.
</P>
<P>
In 1987, Rau, as SPD candidate for German Federal Chancellor,
was defeated by Helmut Kohl. Seven years later he was again
defeated by Roman Herzog, now the outgoing President, in the
federal presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Rau astonished the media and even his close friends in 1982,
when he, long being a bachelor, announced to marry the
granddaughter of ex-President Gustav Heinemann. At that time he
was 51 years old and she was 26. Now the family has three
children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
