<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SPD's Rau Elected German President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 23 (Xinhua)--German Social Democrat (SPD) Johannes
Rau was elected as the country's President by Sunday's
parliamentary session in the historic building of Reichstag in
Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Rau won the election at the second round ballot at which 690
lawmakers voted in favor. He had failed to gain the necessary 670
votes at first round.
</P>
<P>
Other two candidates, both women, were Dagmar Schipanski of
Germany's largest opposition, the conservative Christian
Democratic Union (CDU), and Uta Ranke-Heinemann of the left wing
Democratic Socialist Party (PDS).
</P>
<P>
Schipanski, a physician, had won 588 from 1333 votes in the
first round, while Ranke-Heinemann won 69, and Rau, 657. But in
the second round, some legislators voted in favor Rau.
</P>
<P>
Rau, a moderate SPD politician and former Premier of the North
Rhine-Westphalia State who had been ruling for 20 years, will on
July 1 formally succeed the outgoing President Roman Herzog.
</P>
<P>
In Germany's political life, federal presidency is largely a
ceremonial role with most power be concentrated in the
chancellory.
</P>
<P>
Rau, popular inside the party because of his ability to draw
opposing sides together, is well known as a joke-teller, a keen
christian and a Bible quote.
</P>
<P>
Sunday's election in Berlin coincided with the 50 th
anniversary of Germany's Basic Law, the country's constitution
since 1949.
</P>
<P>
And Parliamentary president Wolfgang Thierse, who presided over
the assembly, depicted it as " the first election for a president
residing in Berlin." 
</P>
</TEXT>
