<HEADLINE> Ugandan President Leaves for COMESA Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni
left here Sunday evening for Kenyan capital Nairobi to attend the
4th summit of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa
(COMESA).
</P>
<P>
A press release issued by the President's Office said that the
president was seen off by Vice-President Specioza Kazibwe at the
Entebbe International Airport.
</P>
<P>
The two-day summit opens in Nairobi Monday to deliberate on
trade issues within the 21 member countries of the regional trade
bloc with a view to achieving zero tariff trade by October 31,
2000.
</P>
<P>
The summit follows a three-day 7th meeting of the COMESA
Council of Ministers which began Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA, set up in 1994, is aiming to realize complete
regional economic integration.
</P>
<P>
The regional trade bloc with a population of 380 million people
and a gross domestic product (GDP) of 155 billion U.S. dollars is
a potential big market.
</P>
<P>
However, its exports valued only 23 billion dollars in 1998,
accounting for less than 0.45 percent of the world's total.
</P>
<P>
The COMESA is trying to promote trade in and outside the
sub-region in a bid to play its role in the globalization in the
new millenium. 
</P>
