<HEADLINE> Alpine Floods Claim up to 7 Lives </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, May 23 (Xinhua)--Seven people have possibly been killed
in floods after days of heavy rain over the Alpine region that
covers southern Germany, northern Austria and Switzerland, more
were missing and thousands were affected, German authorities said
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Two German boot drivers were feared drowned. They had been
missing since Saturday night when their boots had been swept by
roaring rivers.
</P>
<P>
In Germany's southern sate of Bavaria, two pensioners,
respectively 87 and 75 years old, have been found dead after they
had been trapped in flooded cellars.
</P>
<P>
A fifth German, a holidaymaker, was killed in a landslide in
Switzerland. And in Austria, two people were reportedly killed in
floods and mountain slides.
</P>
<P>
Some 100,000 people in Bavaria are affected by the floods,
local officials estimated.
</P>
<P>
"It is a flood of century," said Bavarian Interior Minister
Guenter Beckstein. He said the region was in a state of
"extraordinary emergency".
</P>
<P>
Lake Constance rose to a century high of 5.63 meter, while
other lakes and rivers in central and southern Germany also hit
record heights. Many cities in the region have sounded a
catastrophe alarm.
</P>
<P>
Mud slides blocked roads and railways between Germany and
Austria, and in some areas even power supplies were cut off. Local
motorists are busy seeking alternative means of transport.
</P>
<P>
But the worst was over, said meteorologists of the German
Weather Service. They forecast a dry spell, which will begin on
this Monday and will let the floods run off. 
</P>
</TEXT>
