<HEADLINE> S. African Voters Allowed to Vote Anywhere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Registered voters, who will be
absent from their polling districts on voting day, can cast their
ballot elsewhere in the country, the South African Independent
Electoral Commission said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Howeve$]R,\86y for a declaration vote
from a local electoral official or presiding officer on May 26 or
May 31 to be eligible to do so.
</P>
<P>
Should a voter be outside the province in which he is
registered, such voter would only be entitled to a national ballot
and not a provincial one.
</P>
<P>
Elections for the national and provincial legislatures are to
be held on the same day, June 2.
</P>
<P>
The new arrangements followed an amendment to the Election
Regulations published in Friday's Government Gazette, electoral
officials told a press briefing in Cape Town Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Special votes for those registered voters who would be
overseas on June 2 would take place at South African missions
abroad on May 26, said the electoral commission.
</P>
<P>
These voters would be entitled to a national ballot only, it
added.
</P>
<P>
South African diplomats and members of their household could
also apply for and cast their ballots on May 26.
</P>
<P>
Those who wished to cast a special vote because of physical
infirmity or disability, or pregnancy, would have to apply to a
local electoral officer not later than May 26, or to a presiding
officer on May 26 or 31.
</P>
<P>
Such voters would be visited by electoral officials and would
vote on May 31 or June 1, according to the independent electoral
commission.
</P>
<P>
Electoral officials and security officers deployed for the
elections could apply for and cast their special votes in their
registered districts on May 26, May 31 or June 1. 
</P>
