<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced Sunday that a
parliamentary delegation will travel to Austin, Texas State of the
U.S., on May 25 to intercede with key officials in the case of
Joseph Stanley Faulder, a Canadian who is scheduled to be executed
on June 17.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentarians will seek executive clemency for Mr.
Faulder from the State of Texas. The Canadian government believes
that Faulder's rights were violated when state officials failed to
notify him of his right to contact Canadian consular officials at
the time of his arrest.
</P>
<P>
"Access by Canadian consular officials to Canadians who have
been arrested by foreign governments is an important and
fundamental principle of international law--which in his case was
not respected," said Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd
Axworthy in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The three-MPs delegation will meet with a number of state
officials, including the chairman of the Texas Board of Pardons
and Paroles, the Secretary of State of Texas, and the Deputy
Attorney General for Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
Faulder, 61, was convicted of killing a 75-year-old East Texas
woman 23 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government has been active in the case since 1992.
