<HEADLINE> Lott: U.S. Senate Rejects Ground War Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, May 23 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate will reject the
use of American ground troops to fight Serb forces, but consider
backing plans for a non-combat deployment to help Kosovo refugees
return home, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Lott said the air war's mistakes unfairly are blemishing the
U.S. military, which he said has been sent on a mission in
Yugoslavia that air power alone cannot win.
</P>
<P>
As NATO's bombing against Yugoslavia enters a third month, the
alliance has flown about 26,000 sorties over Yugoslavia, and about
15,000 bombs or missiles. NATO Claimed that its mistake rate is
less than one percent.
</P>
<P>
Lott, appearing on CBS's program, said the bombing is hurting
U.S. prestige.
</P>
<P>
"Quite frankly, these little boo-boos, where you're hitting a
KLA (Kosovol Liberation Army) headquarters, where you're killing
innocent citizens, I think is hurting the image of the military,
which is unfair," Lott said.
</P>
<P>
Lott said Congress should "be supportive of the
(airstrikes-only) decision, now that the decision has been made,
and hope for the best. Absolutely. But I am very dubious about the
likelihood for success just with bombing."
</P>
<P>
Lott made it clear that he opposes sending ground troops to
Kosovo in a combat mode.
</P>
<P>
"If you're talking about fighting their way in there,
absolutely not," Lott said. "The president has repeatedly told the
American people that we would not use ground troops in a combat
mode there." 
</P>
</TEXT>
