<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan President Reaffirms Commitment to Free </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
reaffirmed COMESA's determination to meet its deadline for the
establishment of a " free trade zone" by October 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Moi, the current chairman of the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern African (COMESA), said at the opening ceremony of the
Fourth COMESA Summit in Nairobi that "we should endeavor to honor
the time-table we have so painstakingly worked out for the
realization of a COMESA free trade area by October 31, 2000."
</P>
<P>
The president told the two-day summit, which is attended by 12
heads of government and senior officials from 21 COMESA member
states, that the realization of this objective calls for
commitment as well as sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
According to the African trade body's objectives, all tariff
and non- tariff barriers to trade among its member countries will
be removed by October 31, 2000, and a common external tariff will
be introduced by 2004.
</P>
<P>
Moi said the implementation of this goal has cost implications
on the economies of the member countries. "The governments will
have to forfeits the right to levy taxes on goods imported from
COMESA member countries," he added.
</P>
<P>
The president also stressed, "these are some of the short-term
sacrifices we must make."
</P>
<P>
The out-going COMESA chairman and Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba also reaffirmed the trade bloc's commitment by saying,"a
firm foundation is already being laid for its smooth introduction
and operation."
</P>
<P>
Many observers are sceptical about the objective of the African
sub- regional organization, since there are about one third of its
member countries are still involved in regional or civil
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
COMESA covers a vast area of about 13 million square
kilometers with a population of 380 million, its gross domestic
product is only 165 billion U.S. dollars which is about that of a
small European country like Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian president revealed that 14 COMESA member states
have reduced 60 percent of their tariffs and 10 countries have
reduced tariffs by 80 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
