<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Objectives Can't Be Realized Without Peace, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 24 (Xinhua) --  Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
said the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA)
can not realize its goal of free trade in the region without
peace.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the Fourth COMESA summit
held in Nairobi Monday, Moi said, "we can not talk meaningfully
about improving the standards of living of out people when brother
is rising against brother."
</P>
<P>
Moi, who was elected COMESA chairman replacing out-going
chairman, Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, said that "we can
not strengthen trade between us when wars are destroying
productivity, neither can we improve the well-being of our people
when political instability continues to force thousands of people
to suffer as refugees in neighboring countries."
</P>
<P>
Moi said that the maintenance of peace and security is a
critical ingredient in the trade body's efforts to ensure the
social and economic development in the region.
</P>
<P>
"As we discuss these important issues regarding trade, we must
also make our contributions in addressing the need to strengthen
peace in our region."" Moi said.
</P>
<P>
The two-day summit is attended by 12 head of states of the
regional bloc, including Laurent kabila, President of the war-torn
Democratic Republic of Congo, "
</P>
<P>
Almost one third of the 21-ember regional bloc, like the
Democratic Republic of Congo, Uganda, Rwanda, Namibia ,Zimbabwe,
Ethiopia and Eritrea, are involved in military conflicts in the
region, which makes it hard for COMESA to realize its objectives.
</P>
<P>
COMESA is aiming to realize a full free trade area guaranteeing
the free movement of goods and services produced within COMESA and
the adoption of a common visa arrangements in the regional group.
</P>
<P>
Moi also urged COMESA countries to reduce expenditure on arms
imports which only serve to create employment and increased
incomes for arms manufacturers in distant lands, Moi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
