<HEADLINE> Chinese Police Repatriate Ghana Citizen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Public Security
disclosed today that Chinese police have repatriated Aciieampong,
a citizen of the Republic of Ghana, who attempted to smuggle
himself into Canada via China.
</P>
<P>
On March 11, Aciieampong was stopped by border inspection
officials at the Yantai Airport in east China's Shandong Province
for possession of fake credentials.
</P>
<P>
Police later found that the 37-year-old man, who was
dissatisfied with his poor life in Ghana, had left his hometown
with 3,000 U.S. dollars of family savings and loans.
</P>
<P>
He arrived in Hong Kong last October as a tourist and stayed
there for three months before he obtained a fake United States
passport.
</P>
<P>
Aciieampong planed to enter Canada via Yantai and the Republic
of Korea, but was unexpectedly stopped as soon as he arrived at
the Yantai Airport.
</P>
<P>
He could not return to his hometown as he had spent all his
money in Hong Kong and given his own passport to an accomplice
before his departure from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Chinese police provided free board and lodging and clothes and
medical service for him while his case was under review, in
accordance with the law. After 48 days of efforts, Chinese police
reached an agreement with their counterparts in Ghana and sent
Aciieampong home on April 26.  
</P>
</TEXT>
