<HEADLINE> Greece, China Stand for Political Solution of Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Both Greece and China believe that
the solution to the Kosovo crisis must be a diplomatic and
political one, and diplomatic efforts must be intensified for a
quick resolution, Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou said
here this evening.
</P>
<P>
Papandreou made the remarks at a press conference prior to his
departure for the United States from the Chinese capital.
</P>
<P>
Greece shares much in common with China in its desire for a
political solution of the Kosovo crisis, said the Greek foreign
minister, who arrived here Sunday for a two-day working visit.
</P>
<P>
Before visiting Beijing, Papandreou visited Belgium, France,
Finland, and Russia, to further diplomatic efforts.
</P>
<P>
During Papandreou's stay in Beijing, he met with Chinese Vice
Premier Qian Qichen and Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan to
discuss the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
"We discussed the Kosovo crisis extensively and exchanged views,
" he said, adding that both governments believe there must be a
solution which respects the territorial integrity and sovereignty
of Yugoslavia and the democratic rights of ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
He said that he also discussed some details of a possible
solution to the crisis and other Balkan issues including
reconstruction,as well as the relationship between China and the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
China and Greece have warm relations, Papandreou said, adding
that China has an important voice in world affairs as a permanent
member of the U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"China also wants to contribute in a constructive way as much
as possible to peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Greek foreign minister also expressed the deepest sorrow
for the three Chinese innocent victims of NATO's attack on the
Chinese embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
He said he understood the desire of the Chinese government to
receive a clear and in-depth answer to the incident. 
</P>
