<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Appeal From a Belgrade Pediatric Surgeon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Six brand-new incubators were idle
while four new-born babies were crying weakly with two nurses
looking on in between them without much assistance.
</P>
<P>
Electricity was out for already 10 hours in a run.
</P>
<P>
The University Children's Hospital of Belgrade was without
electricity after NATO warplanes bombed the country's power supply
system outside the capital city over the past two days.
</P>
<P>
The babies were not the only ones affected by the black-out, 84
others were also affected in the hospital, including children
patients of meningitis, leukaemia, serious bone fracture.
</P>
<P>
With 400 beds, the only specially-designed children's hospital
in the capital city now could only manage a daily admission of 10
children compared with 45 before NATO air raids started on March
24. The hospital could now operate on 2 patients instead of on 35
previously, all due to the lack of normal electricity supply.
</P>
<P>
Dusan Scepanovic, general director of the hospital and a senior
professor of pediatric surgery, appealed to the NATO
secretary-general and the United Nations secretary-general for an
immediate stop of NATO bombing against the country's power supply
system.
</P>
<P>
"Electricity and electrically-supported water supply to
hospital are like air to human beings," said the professor. He
would like to know any of his peers in either the United States or
Britain who can continue operating on patients without electricity
or water.
</P>
<P>
Not only operations, medical equipment that needs electricity
and water cannot function normally in the hospital. Bone marrow
transplant, plasma transfusion and one hundred and one other
medical treatments are run on electricity, he said.
</P>
<P>
Scepanovic is now the one who has to decide which children
patients can be operated on the next day but it is to him more
like a judge on life-and-death matters than the routine to a
doctor.
</P>
<P>
"We doctors here can no longer take the responsibility to take
care of all the children patients like this," he said, "The NATO
and the United Nations have to take this responsibility." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
