<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Starts Efforts to Form Coalition Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak's negotiating team on Monday held a meeting with
leaders of the left-wing Meretz Party in efforts to form a
broad-based coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio said the meeting focused on the policy of the
new government, but not on the distribution of the portfolios.
</P>
<P>
David Libai, head of the negotiating team, asked Meretz not to
be hesitative in joining a wide coalition.
</P>
<P>
However, Meretz representatives stressed the coalition
government should not include the religious Shas Party. Meretz
has insisted that it will not join a government with Shas.
</P>
<P>
In the May 17 parliamentary and prime minister elections, Shas,
which represents the ultra-orthodox Jews of Middle East and North
African origin, won 17 seats in the 120-member Knesset
(parliament), and Meretz garnered 10 seats.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Meretz also submitted a list of demands, which
includes an end to the expansion of Jewish settlements in the
occupied territories and the resumption of the peace talks with
Syria and Lebanon, which was stalled in early 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meretz demanded that the negotiations with Syria be resumed
from where they were left off in 1996 under Israel's former Labor
government.
</P>
<P>
The then labor government has accepted the principle of
returning much of the Golan Heights in exchange for security
guarantees and a full peace treaty with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Barak won a landslide victory over outgoing Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu in the May 17 elections. And he has 45 days to
form a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Barak's negotiating team is due to finish the first round of
talks with all the parties this week.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, Barak and his negotiators are to draw up guidelines
for the new government before continuing coalition talks with
concerned parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Africa Seeks for Debt Cancellation (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- A movement for a complete
cancellation of unpayable debt on billions of people is unfolding
as African countries celebrating Africa Freedom Day on May 25.
</P>
<P>
Highly indebted African countries are seeking a new freedom
from the burden as they enter the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
The just-ended regional conference titled "Toward an African
consensus on sustainable solutions to the debt problem" concluded
here by adopting the Lusaka declaration, which urged African
countries to undertake a plan of action leading to debt
cancellation and determine their own development path.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from ten African countries attended the
conference.
</P>
<P>
According to a human development report released by the United
Nations Development Program (UNDP) at the conference, at least 33
countries in Africa are faced with a crippling debt problem that
is now widely acknowledged and for which sustainable solutions are
being sought and worked out.
</P>
<P>
It is also widely accepted that these countries are
experiencing high levels of poverty that need to be addressed.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that sub-Sahara African countries are at the
bottom of human development index. About 260 million people in
the region are subsisting on less than one U.S. dollar per day,
half of the children are not in school, life expectancy is the
lowest in the world at 53 years, infrastructure is dilapidated and
the share of Africa's trade in the world economy had declined from
3.1 percent achieved around the time of independence in the 1960's
to 1.2 percent in 1990's.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a large debt burden motivates a lot of poor
countries to lower labor standards as they engage in a desperate
struggle to attract foreign investment and thereby earn enough
"hard currency" from export revenues to repay foreign debt. That
leads to lower wages and growing poverty around Africa.
</P>
<P>
Each day the poorest countries transfer 717 million dollars in
debt serving to the richest countries, the UNDP said.
</P>
<P>
In order to repay foreign debts, many poor countries are being
forced to direct scarce government resources away from the health
care, education and other vital services.
</P>
<P>
The UNDP estimates that debt serving payments Africa makes
could, if re-directed to expenditure on health care, save the
lives of seven million people a year.
</P>
<P>
Zambia, for instance, spends 200 million dollars annually on
debt servicing, and is likely to be faced with over 600 million
annual debt servicing bills after the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The result has been to deny many children the chance to go to
school, women access to pre-natal care, HIV-infected persons
access to counseling and treatment, and small farmers access to
credit and technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, the people of Zambia, considering its
population of about 10 million, the immense debt burden means that
every woman, man and child owes 650 dollars to international
creditors.
</P>
<P>
Following independence, the proportion of gross national
product (GNP) Zambia devoted to education was one of the highest
in Africa. But now, it is one of the lowest.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique is one of the countries holding the lowest
development indicators in the world. Two-thirds of Mozambican
people live below the poverty line. Yet, it carries a burden of
5.6 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Every year, a quarter of export earning in Mozambique goes to
debt service, the same with the government's revenues. This is
only a third of what the government should be paying. The
scheduled debt service in the period of 1995-1998 averaged 375
dollars per capita. The government only managed to pay 113
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Africa's main creditors are the world's wealthiest nations,
such as the United States, France and Germany. Other important
creditors include the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the
World Bank, which are controlled primarily by the world's rich
nations. Regional development banks and many commercial banks
also have loans to poor nations.
</P>
<P>
Debt arises from credit and aid is a grant. However, there has
been some strange relationship between the two. It has been
observed that the amount of official aid rarely exceeds that of
debt repayments. In some cases donor countries collect more from
countries than they give to them in aid.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, sovereign rights of African countries have been
greatly compromised due to the debt situation. And the various
wars being fought on the African continent are increasing the debt
situation.
</P>
<P>
There is clear consensus that poverty is a problem in Africa
and that the current debt problem plays a significant role in
preventing its eradication. The cause of the debt problem is
shared by both the debtor and creditor. However, it has become a
tool for some creditors to exercise control over African
countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Filipinos Demonstrate Against VFA Outside Senate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 1,000 Filipino peasants,
workers and students rallied in front of the Philippine Senate
Monday afternoon against the Visiting Force Agreement (VFA) that
would allow the resumption of military exercises with U.S. troops
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators held flags and chanted "Junk VFA," "Kill and
Burn VFA" and other anti-American slogans.
</P>
<P>
Some demonstrators threw stones toward policemen and the
Marines in front of the gate of the senate.
</P>
<P>
A worker from Gelmart Industries Philippines said, "Before
Americans come, the Philippines don't have enemy; after they come,
we have."
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Peace and Solidarity Council, one of the
organizers of the demonstration, said in an open letter to the
senate that the VFA "will not only aggravate the present strife
among our people, but will also sow discord within our region."
</P>
<P>
The letter said the VFA is not even in the interest of
President Joseph Estrada's administration, because "the return of
U.S. forces in our country will be like having a gun leveled again
at the head of any Philippine regime."
</P>
<P>
Inside the senate building, Senator Raul Roco said the VFA
"will deny the Filipino equal protection of the law in his own
land" and "there has been no cogent or valid reason given to
accept such an oppressive situation."
</P>
<P>
The VFA, signed by former President Ramos' administration and
the U.S. government, must have the support of at least 16 of the
23 senators for it to pass.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, three senators -- Teofisto Guingona Jr., Serge
Osmena III and Raul Roco -- have expressed their objection to the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Military ties between the Philippines and the United States
have remained sensitive since the Philippine Senate forced the
closure of the last U.S. base in the country in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The senate vote on the VFA was originally scheduled for May 17,
but it has been postponed three times because of strong objection.
The new voting date is May 27, but an official in the senate said
it might be postponed again. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China, Greece Seek Political Solution to Kosovo Issue (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He pointed out that the U.S.-led NATO bombing of Yugoslavia has
caused the greatest humanitarian disaster in Europe, not only
harming security in the Balkans, but also disturbing global peace
and stability.
</P>
<P>
China has always held that the sovereignty and territorial
integrity of Yugoslavia should be respected and the legal rights
of all ethic groups in Kosovo, including those of the Albanian, be
guaranteed, he noted.
</P>
<P>
China has condemned the U.S.-led NATO attack against Yugoslavia
and has demanded that NATO stop bombing at once and bring the
Kosovo issue back to the track of a political solution, he said.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that a political solution will not be possible
unless the bombing ends, and China will not agree with the idea
that the UN discuss a political resolution while the bombing is
still going on.
</P>
<P>
He said that the UN Security Council cannot impose a political
solution on a sovereign state without that state's approval.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-led NATO's attack at the Chinese embassy in Yugoslavia
severely violated China's sovereignty and roughly trampled on the
norms of international law. U.S.-led NATO should take the Chinese
government's solemn demands seriously and give a satisfactory
reply to the Chinese people, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
China is willing to maintain close consultation and
coordination with Greece on the Kosovo crisis and other
international issues, he said. 
</P>
