<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar weakened
Monday, caving into a host of negative factors including gold,
commodities, the Japanese yen and the uncertainty over the future
of the government's goods and services tax (GST) proposal.
</P>
<P>
At the close Monday the Australian dollar was at 65.65 U.S.
cents from 66.13 U.S. cents at Friday's close, having traded
between 65.57 and 65.86 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Nick Volanakis, treasury manager at Colonial State Bank, said
the Australian dollar was sustaining a corrective move amid some
short-term negative influences.
</P>
<P>
"It's a combined thing -- weak yen, weak commodities, weak
gold, still no GST resolution," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was besieged by profit taking and poor
commodity prices on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Prices for copper, lead, zinc and aluminum were lower on the
London Metal Exchange on Friday while gold was again in sight of
20-year lows.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar also closed at 0.6215 euro from 0.6245
euro Friday and 81.39 Japanese yen from 81.86 yen. 
</P>
