<HEADLINE> Greece Asks NATO to Temporarily Stop Transiting Troops </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Greece has asked the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO) to temporarily stop transiting the
alliance troops from the northern Greek port of Thessaloniki to
neighboring Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Confirming a report in the Athens daily "Ta Nea" at a press
briefing Monday, Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas said
that the government had asked NATO to suspend such transit for 12
days, ten before and two after European elections on June 13.
</P>
<P>
He explained that police officers who accompany NATO convoys to
the Greek-Macedonian border will be deployed at different places
during elections.
</P>
<P>
Since the start of the Kosovo crisis, Greece, member of both
NATO and the European Union (EU), has refused to participate
directly in NATO military operations against Yugoslavia, but has
provided the use of Thessaloniki as a transit point for NATO
troops in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
More than 10,000 NATO troops have reportedly passed through
Thessaloniki for Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Reppas also said that Greece and the Czech Republic
had agreed to propose a 48-hour cease-fire in Yugoslavia in order
to give time to diplomatic efforts for acceleration of the Kosovo
peace initiatives.
</P>
<P>
The proposal would be submitted to NATO, which began airstrikes
against Yugoslavia on March 24, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
