<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Africa Seeks for Debt Cancellation (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One of the solutions to the problem is heavily indebted poor
countries (HIPC) initiative, which was sponsored by the IMF and
the World Bank to help provide debt relief in these countries.
</P>
<P>
Under normal HIPC terms, debts in some African countries may be
 cancelled only after a six-year or more qualification period.
</P>
<P>
Regarded by many as ground-breaking when it was introduced two
years ago, HIPC has not lived up to the expectations of many
African governments although five African countries are among the
total of seven countries that have qualified for HIPC debt relief,
out of 41 potential candidates.
</P>
<P>
African countries are unsatisfied with HIPC, saying it might
offer some help, but it comes too late. For instance, Zambia
won't be eligible for HIPC relief until 2002, it is too little,
for only a portion of the debt is written off the books; it is too
limited, only 41 countries are declared "eligible"; and it is too
unrealistic, it doesn't consider social factors.
</P>
<P>
Africa countries reiterate the call for total unpayable debt
cancellation, and insist that creditors and G7 countries cannot be
allowed to dictate the terms of cancellation.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka declaration said HIPC initiative and other debt
relief proposals, including the recent proposals from G7
countries, notably from the United States, Britain and Germany,
all insist on unacceptable conditions, and entail inadequate
amounts of relief.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, it added, the so-called debt relief initiatives have
not resulted from inclusive negotiations. The Paris Club and the
HIPC are merely processes and frameworks imposed by creditors on
debtors.
</P>
<P>
"We reject HIPC and the other current debt relief processes and
commit ourselves to expose their fundamental flaws in each of
countries, particularly in the run-up to the June G8 meeting in
Cologne, Germany," the declaration said, adding "as members of
African civil society, we believe we have the standing to speak
truth to power, in the presence of overwhelming Northern financial
arrogance".
</P>
<P>
Africans believe debt is one of the most important instruments
of Northern domination over the South, and the domination of
financiers over people, production and nature everywhere, it
noted.
</P>
<P>
"As part of our struggle to liberate ourselves from this
bondage, we make demands for the cancellation of debt as part of a
broader struggle to fundamentally transform the current world
economic order and transfer power from the political leadership of
the rich countries, " said the declaration.
</P>
<P>
"In addition, we commit ourselves to working against localized
symptoms of our debt burden and economic process, including war,
corruption and other evils that undermine our development
process," it added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a world-wide anti-debt campaign, organized by the
Jubilee 2000 group, is underway to lobby donor countries and
international lending institutions to cancel the unpayable debt
for the impoverished countries of the world by the next
millennium, saying it wants to collect about 22 million signatures
at next month's meeting of G7/8, and press the leaders to consider
canceling the debt of the Third World countries.
</P>
<P>
In Zambia, the debt cancellation campaign has gained momentum
on May 22 through a solidarity march in various parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Religious Affairs Deputy Minister Peter Chintala said
here after taking part in the march that the country's
6.5-billion-dollar debt had not only become unpayable but also
unserviceable.
</P>
<P>
He said it was encouraging to note that 180,000 signatures in
favor of debt cancellation had been obtained from various
individuals in the country and the government was happy to know
that it had support from citizens.
</P>
<P>
He called on African countries to adopt a common strategy
toward IMF and World Bank conditionalities and foster cooperation
through economic integration in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
