<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Close Slightly Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket ended
marginally weaker Monday after investors remained concerned about
the possibility of interest rate rises in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark All Ordinaries Index fell 1.5 points to 2,949.2
after jumping between positive and negative territory during the
day.
</P>
<P>
"There were not very many people coming in bargain hunting
today," Lucinda Chan from Macquarie Equities said.
</P>
<P>
"The market's very edgy, very nervous. There's a lot of talk
over there (in the United States) about the market pulling back a
lot more if rates go up, so people are still a bit worried about
that," she said.
</P>
<P>
In Australia on Monday, the All Industrials Index fell 5.8
points to 5,175.7 while the All Resources Index moved in the
opposite direction adding 3.1 points to 1,175.5, despite a fall in
the gold sector.
</P>
<P>
The biggest four banks in Australia were mostly lower with the
Commonwealth of Australia losing 14.2 cents to 24.508 Australian
dollars, the National Australia Bank down 15.2 cents to 25.1
Australian dollars and the ANZ bank sliding 2.7 cents to 11.37
Australian dollars. Westpac bank added 4 cents to 10.64 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, diversified miner BHP lost 3.6 cents
to 16.994 Australian dollars while global miner Rio Tinto gained
40.2 cents to 24 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold sector fell 17.4 points to 914.5 and the spot price of
gold bullion in Sydney Monday closed at 272.65 U.S. dollars an
ounce, from Friday's close of 275.25 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 316.41 million shares worth 499.64
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Falls outnumbered rises 702 to 519, with 527 remaining steady.
 
</P>
