<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's TradeNet Passes Y2K Tests, Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's Trade Development
Board (TDB) declared Monday that its on-line trade documentation
system, TradeNet, has passed a six-day Y2K test and will be ready
to handle the year 2000 and the leap year processing of trade
documentation.
</P>
<P>
TDB's Director for Computer Information Services Division
Martin Tsang said in a press release that the TradeNet Y2K
Integrated Simulation Test was declared a success after six days
of stress testing from May 10 to 15.
</P>
<P>
During the test, more than 500 trade documentation cases were
tested with the participation of the TDB, the Customs and Excise
Department (CED), Singapore Network Services (SNS), Cargo
Community Network (CCN), nine controlling agencies, four TradeNet
software vendors and 10 of their shipping agents and traders.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said, "We are pleased at the success of the simulation
exercises and it will still be business as usual for our traders
as we enter the year 2000."
</P>
<P>
Tsang also said two minor problems were encountered and quickly
resolved during the test.
</P>
<P>
They were the communication problem which obstructed the
connectivity between Customs and Excise Department and Singapore
Network Services and the permit date problem which made TradeNet
System unable to format some permits correctly when the system was
set to February 28, 2000, and February 29, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Tsang was confident that TDB's services will continue to run
smoothly without any disruptions as it crosses over into the year
2000.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K problem arises when software records the year in two
digits instead of four, which will cause confusion when the year
2000 approaches. 
</P>
</TEXT>
