<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian President Hails Progress Made by COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 24 (Xinhua) -- As of February 1, 1999, 14 out of
the 21 member states of the Common Market for Eastern and Southern
Africa (COMESA) had reduced their tariffs by 60 percent. Of
them, 10 countries had reduced COMESA tariff by 80 percent or
more.
</P>
<P>
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba made these remarks in his
keynote address delivered at the 4th Summit of COMESA Authority
opened here Monday. The two-day summit is attended by over a
dozen heads of state and government from the COMESA members.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, the outgoing chairman of the COMESA Authority who has
served the regional body during the past two years, said COMESA
had made commendable progress toward the attainment of the goals
of a free trade area by October 31, 2000 and a common external
tariff by the year 2004.
</P>
<P>
Over the last two years, Chiluba said, "we have pursued the
goal of creating a common market where goods, services, labor and
capital are free to move across our borders."
</P>
<P>
To facilitate the operations of a free trade area, the COMESA
had implemented programs including those intended to facilitate
transportation, communication, business transactions and
investment in the region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Transport programs embracing road, rail, sea and air transport
are being implemented and indications showed that the program had
considerably reduced the cost of moving goods in the region.
</P>
<P>
With regards to the clearing house, Chiluba noted that the
introduction of faster and easier payment system would greatly
facilitate business transactions. In addition, the clearing
house would provide an innovative political risk guarantee scheme,
namely, the proposed Africa Guarantee Facility.
</P>
<P>
COMESA has established the Consultative Committee of the
Business Community and implemented the Regional Investors' Road
Map which have greatly facilitated the investors to conduct
cross-border investment projects and the development of the
private sector, Chiluba said.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed potential investors within and outside the region
to invest in COMESA sectors such as telecommunications,
information technology, tourism, mining and agro-business.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian president also cited some progress COMESA has made
over the past two years in the fields of free movement of people
and labors,

legislation, and increased cooperation with international and
regional development partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
