<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Top Lawmaker Stresses Supervision (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, May 24 (Xinhua) -- China's top lawmaker Li Peng has
stressed the importance of strengthening supervision over the
government and judicial organs, saying that this is the common
aspiration of Chinese lawmakers and the majority of the people.
</P>
<P>
"Deputies to people's congresses at all levels and the broad
masses of the people all require the supervisory work to be
further strengthened and to enact a law on supervision as early as
possible," said Li, chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature, during
his study tour of the east China province of Shandong last week.
</P>
<P>
Li, also a Standing Committee member of the Political Bureau of
the Communist Party of China (CPC) Central Committee, mainly
learned about the supervisory work of the local people's
congresses and their standing committees during the tour of Jinan,
capital of Shandong, and several other cities.
</P>
<P>
He also called several meetings to solicit opinions on a draft
of the Regulations on the Supervision on the Judicial Organs'
Handling of Some Individual Cases, which was formulated recently
by the NPC Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
Li told participants in the meetings that during the second
annual full session of the Ninth NPC convened in Beijing in March,
many Chinese legislators had called for intensified supervision on
the government and judicial bodies.
</P>
<P>
"The NPC Standing Committee has attached utmost importance to
their suggestions and has decided to enact a Law on Supervision
during its five-year term of office," he added.
</P>
<P>
Before the law is worked out and formally adopted, Li said, the
NPC Standing Committee has found it necessary to first enact
several special regulations and legal decisions on supervision,
such as the one he brought for discussion, to pave the way for the
law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
