<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong-based Heritage Fund Invests in Palace Garden Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong-based China Heritage
Fund (CHF) plans to pour four million U.S. dollars into the
reconstruction of the Jianfu Palace Garden in the Imperial Palace
Museum (the Forbidden City).
</P>
<P>
The fund today signed a contract agreement with the China
Heritage Exchange Association to carry out its first relics-
protection project, and the Palace Museum will organize the
reconstruction over the next four years.
</P>
<P>
The Jianfu Palace Garden covers some 4,000 square meters and is
the second largest garden in the Palace complex. It was created in
1740 and was totally destroyed by a disastrous fire in 1923.
</P>
<P>
"Garden reconstruction is an important step in restoring the
former appearance of the ancient Forbidden City," said Zhang
Wenbin, head of the State Administration of Cultural Heritage (
SACH) and also the association president.
</P>
<P>
Ronnie Chan, the CHF chairman, said, "We're devoted to
preserving the treasured cultural relics and ancient architecture.
"
</P>
<P>
"I hope overseas visitors will be able to learn more about
traditional Chinese culture and history," said Chan, chairman of
the Hang Lung Group of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A museum task force has carefully researched the garden ruins
and has sought the advice of many well-known archeologists and
architects.
</P>
<P>
A total of 24 emperors of the Ming (1368-1644) and Qing (1644-
1911) dynasties lived in the enormous palace, built in 1420. The
Imperial Palace Museum in downtown Beijing was placed on the
United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization'
s (UNESCO) World Heritage list in 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
