<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Team Arrives in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- A nine-member U.N. team has arrived
in East Timor on Monday, along with communications equipment for
direct autonomy ballot monitoring, the official Antara News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The team was welcomed by officials of the East Timor
Immigration Office, the report quoted a source at the airport as
saying.
</P>
<P>
It will monitor the direct ballot in East Timor scheduled for
early August this year.
</P>
<P>
Under the U.N. Assessment Mission in East Timor, the United
Nations will send a 600-member mission to execute the process of
consulting the East Timorese on the solution to the East Timor
issue, based on an agreement reached by Indonesia and Portugal in
a recent U.N.-brokered tripartite meeting.
</P>
<P>
The mission will implement the direct balloting to decide
whether or not the East Timorese are willing to accept a
wide-ranging autonomy offered by the Indonesian government. A
rejection of the offer would mean independence for the former
Portuguese territory.
</P>
<P>
All U.N. staff to be deployed in East Timor in preparation for
the ballot should be in place by mid-June.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said here Monday that
Indonesian security forces will be responsible for the security in
East Timor and safety of U.N. personnel.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, with a population of some 800,000 and an area of
15,000 square kilometers, had been a Portuguese colony until 1975
and it became an Indonesian province in 1976. But the United
Nations never recognized the move. 
</P>
</TEXT>
