<HEADLINE> HK Consumer Price Indices for April 1999 Decrease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong consumer prices
registered a year-on-year decrease of 3.8 percent in April 1999,
higher than the 2.6 percent decline in March, the Census and
Statistics Department said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Releasing the Consumer Price Index (CPI) Monday, a Government
Secretariat spokesman noted that consumer prices remained on a
declining trend in April 1999, along with the continuing cost and
price adjustment in the economy.
</P>
<P>
Price discounts continued to be commonly offered at the local
retail outlets, the spokesman said. At the same time, there was a
further softening in import prices, he added.
</P>
<P>
The reduction in the prices of some newspapers and in the
charges of long-distance telephone calls also partly contributed,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Compared with March 1999, the Composite CPI for April 1999
decreased by 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
Taking the first four months of 1999 together, the Composite
CPI decreased by 2.3 percent compared with the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
For the 3 months up to April 1999, the Composite CPI fell by 2.
7 percent compared with the same period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
For the 12 months up to April 1999, the Composite CPI was 0.4
percent higher than that in the preceding 12-month period.
</P>
<P>
The seasonally adjusted average monthly rates of change in the
Composite CPI, during the 3-month period ending April 1999 was -0.
5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
