<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Priority to Coastal Areas in Developing Nuclear Power </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- China will give priority to
southern and eastern coastal areas in developing nuclear power,
said Xu Yuming, deputy director of the State Atomic Energy Agency
(SAEA).
</P>
<P>
The coastal areas, lack of energy resources, have witnessed
fast economic growth over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
Xu said that China will adhere to unified planning when
developing nuclear power so as to keep its step with the
development of electricity and other energy resources.
</P>
<P>
China will make full use of its own nuclear resources and
enhance its capacity of extracting and processing natural uranium,
designing, building and running nuclear power stations and
facilities, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that China will also continue to adopt advanced and
fully-developed nuclear power technology and gradually develop its
new generation of advanced nuclear power stations.
</P>
<P>
Specialists estimate that China will need 20 million kwh and 50
million kwh of power produced by nuclear power stations or
stations using other energy resources respectively in 2010 and
2020 so as to meet the need of social and economical growth.
</P>
<P>
China's nuclear power development has slowed down due to the
competition of other energy resources, Xu said. However, nuclear
power, as a high-quality and clean energy, has irreplaceable
advantages in easing environmental and ecological problems.
</P>
<P>
"Its development still has much room in the future," he added.
</P>
<P>
China plans to construct four nuclear power stations with a
total generating capacity of 6.6 million kw during the 1996-2000
period, all in eastern and southern coastal areas.
</P>
<P>
China currently has a nuclear power generating capacity of 2.1
million kw. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
