<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Filipinos Protest Visiting Forces Pact With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- About 200 protesters, demonstrating
against the Visiting Forces Agreement (VFA) between the
Philippines and the United States, Friday clashed with police
outside the U.S. Embassy in Manila.
</P>
<P>
The activists ran past police lines and destroyed a plastic
cover protecting the U.S. government seal at the embassy's
entrance, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
Police pushed them back with shields and truncheons, injuring
at least one protester, they said.
</P>
<P>
The protesters carried an effigy of U.S. President Bill Clinton
which they later blasted with firecrackers outside the gates,
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
The protesters later marched to join other protesters at the
nearby senate building, where legislators were debating the VFA
that would allow the resumption of large-scale joint military
exercises with U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
The entire Metro Manila police force was on full alert on
Monday in anticipation of massive protest actions against the
ratification of the VFA.
</P>
<P>
Police and military units have been ordered to monitor closely
all ongoing activities and to take necessary and appropriate
action.
</P>
<P>
Last week, senate security forces and police clashed with some
300 anti-VFA demonstrators who tried to storm the senate building.
</P>
<P>
The VFA, signed by Manila and Washington last year, would pave
the way for the resumption of large-scale annual joint military
exercises between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Senate is due to vote on the agreement on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The opponents say the pact gives Washington jurisdiction over
U.S. troops who may commit crimes in the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
They say the pact also exposes the Philippines to nuclear
threats because it does not require the United States to declare
whether it has nuclear weapons aboard visiting ships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
