<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Urges "Firm Decision" on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Viktor Chernomyrdin, the Russian
special envoy for the Balkans, on Monday called for a "firm
decision" on Kosovo, warning a stop to negotiations on the
Yugoslav crisis would spell "catastrophe."
</P>
<P>
"Peace talks are extremely difficult to conduct in light of
the escalation of missile and bomb strikes on Yugoslavia,"
Chernomyrdin told reporters following his meeting with Indian
Foreign Minister Jaswant Singh, who arrived here Sunday for a
visit.
</P>
<P>
He called for coordination of settlement efforts by Russia,
India and China, adding that Moscow is ready for such coordinated
actions.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin said intense talks over the past three weeks have
made NATO accept the fact that part of Serbian troops could remain
in Kosovo, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The troops need to be withdrawn, but it is necessary to leave
part of the troops there, too," he said.
</P>
<P>
Singh, for his part, said New Delhi's stance on the Kosovo
crisis coincided with that of Russia and China and that the Kosovo
conflict is a problem of not only the Balkans, but of the whole
world.
</P>
<P>
The conflict puts in question the role of the United Nations
and the foundations of international law, the foreign minister
said.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin confirmed that he would meet Finnish President
Martti Ahtisaari and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott
here Wednesday for a fresh round of talks over Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
