<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi Urges for African Unity to Achieve Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi
said here Monday that the path of Cooperation and free trade is
the long-term solution to economic problems in the African region.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the opening ceremony of the Fourth Summit of the
Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa(COMESA), Moi said,
"we cannot expect to achieve meaningful economic progress when we
are divided, or if we continue to approach international issues as
individual nations."
</P>
<P>
Though the trade block covers a vast area of about 13 million
square kilometers with a population of 380 million, its gross
domestic product has only 165 billion U.S. dollars which is about
that of a small European country like Belgium.
</P>
<P>
The president told the two-day summit, which was attended by 12
heads of state of its 21 members, that the economy of the African
trade body is extremely vulnerable to the existing constraints in
the global economic progress.
</P>
<P>
Moi, who was elected COMESA chairman replacing the out-going
COMESA Chairman Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, said that
African countries need to put in place "effective strategies",
which will enable them to meet the challenges and harness the
emerging opportunities brought up by global economy.
</P>
<P>
To achieve sustainable growth that will enable African
countries participate effectively and gain from the global
economy, "African countries must work for freedom in trade", Moi
said.
</P>
<P>
The current COMESA chairman said the ongoing summit "is a step
forward in the pursuit of our cherished and common goals."
</P>
<P>
Moi reaffirmed the African sub-regional economic body's
determination to meet its goal for creation of a free trade zone
by october 31, 2000 by removing all tariff and non-tariff barriers
to trade among member countries, and introducing a common external
tariff by 2004.
</P>
<P>
The president also stressed the need to develop common
strategies in the on-going negotiations under the World Trade
Organization and a common stand on the evolving relations between
African, Caribbean and Pacific countries and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis has reduced the economies growth of
many of African countries by up to 50 percent, while the drop of
the prices of primary commodities has further eroded the export
earning of many countries in the region, Moi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
