<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Top Official Depressed by Slow Progress Over Aborigines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Australian Governor-General
William Deane risked angering the Australian federal government
Monday when he said he was depressed by the slow progress in
reconciliation between white Australians and black aborigines.
</P>
<P>
With National Sorry Day being celebrated mainly by the
aborigines on Wednesday, the governor-general, basically a
ceremonial political figure in Australia, again highlighted the
plight of indigenous Australians and his concerns about the
reconciliation process, the Australian Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
"These days, it is sometimes difficult not to feel discouraged
-- even depressed -- about the slow course of the reconciliation
process," he said in Australia's third largest city of Brisbane,
East Australia.
</P>
<P>
He said the country's 300,000 indigenous people were greatly
disadvantaged compared with other Australians in health, welfare,
housing, community services and employment.
</P>
<P>
"In that regard, it is unnecessary to do more than quote one
plain statistic: an aboriginal baby born in this country today
has, on present figures and on average, a life expectancy of
almost 20 years less than that of a non-aboriginal baby," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Think of that: almost 20 years. And the statistics indicate
that the discrepancy is still widening."
</P>
<P>
He apologized in 1997 for the misery of the stolen generations
during half a century before the 1970s under the white
assimilation policy. Tens of thousands of aboriginal children were
forcibly taken from their families and raised in government-funded
welfare centers or churches. Many of whom have never reunited with
their parents.
</P>
<P>
Some of the children, better known as stolen generations, have
been demanding a formal apology from the Australian government for
the misery they had suffered, but the demand was rejected by
Australian Prime Minister John Howard.
</P>
<P>
During the first 100 years of European settlement in Australia,
thousands of innocent aborigines had been killed and many more had
been driven by white people to remote and arid areas.
</P>
<P>
In late 1997 the governor-general inflamed debate on a
government's native title legislation designed to limit
aborigines' claims to land rights by saying he would weep for the
nation if it failed to acknowledge past oppression of aborigines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
