<HEADLINE> Australia, Japan Sign Wheat Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Japan will buy at least 900,000
tons of Australian wheat next year under an agreement signed by
the Australian Wheat Board Ltd. (AWB) and the Japan Food Agency
(JFA).
</P>
<P>
AWB Ltd. Chief Executive Murray Rogers said he hoped JFA, part
of Japan's Agriculture Ministry, would buy more than 1 million
tons of wheat as it had in the previous years.
</P>
<P>
"It's really a minimum target which we can both work toward,"
Rogers said in a statement Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said the agreement is in effect a renewal of the 1998
contract which outlined minimum tonnage.
</P>
<P>
AWB had agreed to supply 200,000 tons of prime hard wheat from
the states of Queensland and New South Wales, East Australia, and
700,000 tons of Australian standard white blend from Western
Australia state under the agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
