<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Open More Consular Offices in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kuala Lumpur, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will open more
consular offices in China for issuance of visas to Chinese
intending to visit the country, Deputy Prime Minister Abdullah
Ahmad Badawi said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
These offices would be located in cities with high demand for
Malaysian visas, said Abdullah, who is also home minister.
</P>
<P>
At present, Chinese can apply for Malaysian visas at the
Malaysian Embassy in Beijing and Malaysian consulates in Hong Kong
and Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
"We have no problem in giving visas to Chinese tourists to
enter Malaysia through the KLIA, Langkawi, Johor Baharu or any
other entry points," he said.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah told reporters this after launching the book "A New
Deal For Asia" written by Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said that as the practice in China is to require
outward-bound Chinese to have visas issued well in advance, it
would be a boon to have more consular offices in that country.
</P>
<P>
Replying to another question, Abdullah said the decision to
have the extra consular offices only is applicable to China.
</P>
<P>
He said Chinese visitors entering Malaysia through a third
country, such as Indonesia, would be given visas at Malaysian
entry points.
</P>
<P>
On the 25th anniversary of Malaysia-China diplomatic ties,
Abdullah said, Malaysia is pleased that the long-established and
cordial ties have benefited both sides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
