<HEADLINE> S. Africa Not to Export Arms to Libya: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 24 (Xinhua) -- South African arms producer,
Denel, has denied any suspicion that it will offer its arms to
Libya, Business Day newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
A high-profile South African trade delegation headed by Trade
and Industry Minister Alec Erwin is visiting Libya, seeking
business contracts and orders.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of the arms parastatal Denel are among the
powerful delegation.
</P>
<P>
Upon his departure for Tripoli on Sunday, Denel chief executive
Max Sisulu denied the trip was to market weapons to Libya.
</P>
<P>
Denel comprised 22 companies which sold a wide range of
equipment, including soya bean processing, money counters and
information technology, said Sisulu.
</P>
<P>
He said South Africa's world class equipment for clearing
landmines, was among the products he would be punting in Libya,
where thousands of landmines planted during the Second World War
posed a serious problem.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources said South African businessmen are hoping to
secure contracts worth billions of U.S. dollars which are up for
grabs since the suspension of the United Nations' sanctions
against Libya.
</P>
<P>
The suspension followed Libya's handover of two men suspected
of the 1988 bombing of the PanAm flight over Lockerbie in Scotland
for trial in the Netherlands, a settlement which South Africa
helped broker. The Lockerbie air crash claimed 270 lives.
</P>
</TEXT>
