<HEADLINE> Macao Faces Brighter Future: First Chief Executive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Edmund Ho Hau Wah, the first chief
executive of the Macao Special Administrative Region (SAR),
believes that with the motherland's backing, there is no doubt
that Macao will have a better future after it returns to the
motherland.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of his new mission, Ho, who is now in Beijing
receiving his official appointment from the State Council, said
that "the responsibility is heavy and the road ahead is long".
</P>
<P>
"This is the same for the Macao people, as well," Ho told
Xinhua in an exclusive interview here today. "Only by trusting
the government and the Macao people will we be able to make a
clear distinction between the right and wrong, will be open and
fair, and will win trust and support, and there will be no burden
or contradiction that will baffle me," Ho said.
</P>
<P>
Ho, 44, was elected the first chief executive of the Macao SAR
on May 15. He is the general manager of the Tai Fung Bank and
chairman of the Macao Association of Banks.
</P>
<P>
Ho took his election as an indication of being trusted by the
Macao people, and said this has given him a great opportunity to
deepen his feelings for the motherland and Macao.
</P>
<P>
"I'll turn the opportunity into selfless sacrifice," said Ho.
</P>
<P>
On the future of Macao, Ho said that two points should be made
clear to the people of Macao -- first, there is no doubt about a
brighter future for Macao, and second, creating prosperity and
making progress requires the concerted effort of the Macao people.
</P>
<P>
"The SAR government will do its utmost to improve the current
situation and push forward social development, and the Macao
people are expected to actively create conditions for the future
development of Macao," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Currently, public security and the economy are the two issues
demanding most attention," Ho said. "People in Macao wish for
early solutions to these problems, and the SAR government will
make efforts to rectify the security order as quickly as possible.
"
</P>
<P>
"But 'Rome was not built in a day' and people should not
expect all problems to be solved overnight when the SAR government
is officially formed," Ho said.
</P>
<P>
"Macao is a small place with limited resources, but its
connections with the rest of the world are extensive and tourism
is booming. Macao is an important bridge and window between Asia,
and the inland areas of the motherland in particular, and the rest
of the world."
</P>
<P>
"Macao expects a broader space in which it can conduct
cooperation with Guangdong and Hong Kong," Ho said, "and its role
as a bridge across the Taiwan Straits will also be displayed
further."
</P>
<P>
"All these advantages will be conducive to Macao's economic
revitalization and stable development, and I am confident that
this is so," Ho concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
