<HEADLINE> Capital Investment Exceeds 2 Billion US Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Total capital investment
approved in Malaysia has reached 8.8 billion ringgit (2.3 billion
U.S. dollars) so far this year.
</P>
<P>
"The amount (of investments) approved has almost touched 10
billion ringgit in the first few months of this year," said Deputy
Minister of International Trade and Industry Kerk Choo Ting here
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The investments are mainly in the electronic and electrical
sector as well as chemical and petrochemical products, he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Kerk said that of the approved amount, 7 billion ringgit (1.8
billion dollars) worth of investments were obtained since April
and they came from two local companies and five foreign investors,
mostly from the United States.
</P>
<P>
Major sources of foreign investments were the United States,
Japan, Taiwan, Singapore and Germany, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kerk said Malaysia will continue to encourage new foreign
investors as well as reinvestments from existing foreign investors
to build upon the industrial foundation that has been laid so far.
</P>
<P>
"The thrust of the industrialization policy will be focused on
the growth and development of industries that will provide maximum
spin-off effects to the economy and the promotion of higher
quality investments and productivity-driven growth," he said.
</P>
<P>
As such, future thrusts will be focused on accelerating the
shift toward hi-tech and knowledge-based industries and developing
resource-based industries which will generate greater domestic
value-added activities, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
