<HEADLINE> OAU Chief Calls for African Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Salim Ahmed Salim, Secretary
General of the Organization of African Unity (OAU), Monday called
on African states

"to close their ranks and work together in the spirit of unity and
 solidarity."
</P>
<P>
The spirit has inspired the founding fathers and sustained the
continental organization over the past 36 years, he said.
</P>
<P>
In his message issued on the occasion of the 36th anniversary
of the founding of the OAU which falls on May 25, Salim said over
the years, the pan-African organization "proved to be an
invaluable instrument for unity and solidarity of the Africans."
</P>
<P>
"Whenever the African peoples stood and acted together, their
voice was heard and their views were taken into account," he said.
</P>
<P>
Salim noted that "today, more than ever before, the unity and
solidarity of Africa is needed to address the formidable
challenges confronting the continent at a time when the world is
experiencing rapid changes."
</P>
<P>
The various conflicts in Africa have caused the loss of
precious lives, destruction and immense suffering to Africans,
Salim said, adding "we have no option but to continue and redouble
our collective efforts to promote peace, security and stability
both in our countries and in our continent."
</P>
<P>
"Our primary objective of promoting the well-being and progress
of our people cannot be achieved in an environment devoid of
peace, security and stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
He, therefore, suggested that the motto for Africans, as they
usher into the new millennium, should be the attainment of lasting
peace, security and stability by all means.
</P>
<P>
The OAU chief appealed to African states "to recommit
themselves to the ideals of unity, solidarity, cooperation and
Pan-Africanism which are enshrined in the OAU charter. 
</P>
</TEXT>
