<HEADLINE> Five Killed in Plane Crash in Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kuala Lumpur, May 24 (Xinhua) -- A Royal Malaysian Air Force
(RMAF) Canadian-made Caribou transport aircraft crashed shortly
after taking off from the Kuching International Airport on Monday,
killing all the five people aboard, a RMAF spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
RMAF Public Relations Officer Maj. Ramli Abdul Rahim said in a
statement issued here that the aircraft was on a normal training
mission when it crashed.
</P>
<P>
"All five crew members are killed and their names will be
released after the RMAF informed their next of kin," he said.
</P>
<P>
Eye-witnesses said an explosion was heard as the aircraft went
down Monday afternoon over a swampy area at the end of the runway,
about 10 kilometers away from the Sarawak state capital, reports
reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
The Caribou is a twin-engined, short take-off and landing
utility transport and is used primarily for tactical airlift
missions in forward battle areas with short, unimproved airstrips.
</P>
<P>
Following the crash, the Kuching International Airport was
closed for 30 minutes, an airport spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
