<P>
The move came after the west African country's deficits hit a
record high, and its foreign currency being alarmingly low, the
Fund's Abuja office confirmed to Xinhua Monday.
</P>
<P>
The threat means the incoming civilian government may go deep
into an economic crisis, since the new administration is still
counting on the IMF to help write off a large bulk of its
29-billion-U.S. dollar foreign debt, inherited from former
Nigerian government.
</P>
<P>
Britain and the United States have both ruled out debt
forgiveness for Nigeria, implying that the new administration must
look to the multinational financial organizations for help.
</P>
<P>
The IMF officials had recommended in a memo to its head office
in Washington that the Nigerian government make an urgent freeze
in the parastatals money in the banking sector as well as the
extra-budgetary spending, reported This Day, one of the country's
leading daily.
</P>
<P>
The memo said the Nigerian government has gone completely off
the track in the implementation of the IMF-sponsored programs.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has always insisted that Nigeria must first show a
six-month record of its healthy economic running --a "clean bill"
as called by some Nigerian commentators, before it could get
further consideration in relieving the country's huge debt stocks,
which is widely deemed to be critical for the success of the new
government's economic policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
