<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Launch 3 Satellites Simultaneously </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, May 24 (Xinhua) -- India is expected to launch three
satellites simultaneously Wednesday and the countdown for the
launch began Monday, the Indian Space Research Organization (ISRO)
said.
</P>
<P>
The country's latest generation space launcher, Polar Satellite
Launch Vehicle (PSLV-C2), will launch an Indian remote sensing
satellite (IRS-P4), a German scientific satellite and a South
Korean satellite on May 26.
</P>
<P>
The 1,050-kg IRS-P4, also called Oceansat-1, will be placed in
a polar sun-synchronous circular orbit of 720 km, at an
inclination of 98.28 degrees, sources said.
</P>
<P>
It will be the first time for ISRO to launch three satellites
in a single vehicle.
</P>
<P>
The IRS-P4 will gather data for oceanographic and atmospheric
applications, develop new application areas and provide
opportunity for conducting technological/scientific experiments
that are of relevance for future development, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
The May 26 launch will also mark India's entry into the highly
profitable business of commercial space launch as the two
non-Indian satellites will be put in space at a promotional price
compared with the international price tag of one million U.S.
dollars per satellite of this class. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
