<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Alatas: U.N. to Assist E. Timor in Autonomy Ballot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations (U.N.) will send
600 personnel to East Timor during the autonomy balloting to be
held there in August this year, Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a news briefing at the Foreign Ministry, Alatas said the
U.N. together with the Indonesian government will be responsible
for the security situation and a smooth implementation of the
autonomy ballot in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. personnel include 400 people who will arrange
the balloting and 200 civil guards to maintain security situation.
</P>
<P>
Under an agreement signed by Indonesia and Portugal on May 5 in
New York, the U.N. will deploy civilian police advisers from
several countries to assist Indonesian police in maintaining law
and order in East Timor. A key function will be the disarmament of
rival factions that are either for or against independence.
</P>
<P>
Alatas was convinced that the security situation will be under
control during the balloting.
</P>
<P>
He said that Indonesia, Portugal and the U.N. are discussing
the problems on sending observers to East Timor to supervise the
balloting, sending emergency hospital units and emergency medical
units there and other technical issues.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. had proposed to send 20 observers to East Timor during
the balloting, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
About 45 million U.S. dollars will be needed to conduct the
ballot and some of them will be provided by the U.N. and several
countries such as Australia, said Alatas.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he said, 200 registration offices and 700 polling
stations will be set up for the balloting.
</P>
<P>
He said a U.N. mission will arrive in Jakarta on May 27 to
discuss the new developments in East Timor and the arrangement for
the direct autonomy ballot. On May 29, he said, the mission will
visit Dili, capital city of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Alatas also denied the reports that the balloting date has
changed from August 8 to August 7. It was only a proposal from the
Indonesian government to the U.N. given August 8 is a Sunday and
the East Timorese will go to church, no decision has been made on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to give East Timorese wide-ranging autonomy by
holding a direct balloting was announced by the Indonesian
government in January this year. The announcement said the
Indonesian government is ready to release East Timor if the
alternative to provide wider autonomy is refused by the people in
the region and the international community.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, with a population of some 800,000 and an area of
15,000 square kilometers, had been a Portuguese colony until 1975.
It became an Indonesian province in 1976, but the U.N. never
recognizes the move.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
