<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lhalu: An Eyewitness of Old and New Tibet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lhalu said, "I stepped out of the jail into the street. To my
surprise, I saw happy people, instead of the beggars who filled
the street in old Tibet."
</P>
<P>
"The Central Government gave me a house with glass windows in
Lhasa, I asked for land to till, and was given 0.3 hectares. I
learned to do farm work," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In June 1978, my wrist watch was lost while I worked in the
field. I told myself not to make a fuss about this as I was a serf
owner in the past. One and a half months later, I was told that my
wrist watch was found by a boy who turned it over to the local
police. The local police worked hard to locate the owner and
finally found it was me," he said.
</P>
<P>
When Lhalu and some others who used to be in the upper strata
of Tibetan society were organized to visit other parts of Tibet,
Lhalu discovered starling changes. Shannan sold mountains of
surplus grain to the State and Nyingchi, a barren area in the past,
was home to more than 100 enterprises in the textile, power
generating and printing fields.
</P>
<P>
"From these I came to understand that the Democratic Reform is
a must," said Lhalu. "The Tibetan race will enjoy a bright future
under CPC rule and by taking the socialist road."
</P>
<P>
In 1977, Lhalu was elected a member of the National Committee
of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC)
and in April 1983, he was elected vice-chairman of the CPPCC Tibet
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Lhalu has completed his lengthy memoirs entitled Rise and Fall
of the Lhalu Clan. "I committed crimes against the Tibetan people.
Over the past four decades following the peaceful liberation of
Tibet, however, the CPC and the people didn't show any prejudice
against me," said Lhalu.
</P>
<P>
"The Tibetans, under the leadership of the CPC and with the
support of the Chinese people as a whole, have driven the
imperialist forces out of the region and China at large."
</P>
<P>
"I lead a comfortable life now. I miss my colleagues who are
still exiled. There is a Tibetan saying: Old bird misses forests
and old people miss hometown," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
