<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets New Regulations of Trust Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- China's Finance Ministry and the
People's Bank of China, the country's central bank, have jointly
issued a circular on the rectification of China's trust and
investment companies, today's China Securities reported.
</P>
<P>
The circular sets new regulations governing appraisal of
properties and funds, assets assessment, and write-off of bad
assets in a bid to protect the legal rights and interests of all
parties concerned, including owners, operators and creditors of
the trust and investment companies, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The appraisal and assessment work on national trust and
investment companies must be conducted under the guidance of the
central bank and special panels from the central government, while
regional companies are subject to appraisals and check-ups
organized by local governments.
</P>
<P>
Regional governments and State Council departments concerned
are required to recommend a group of qualified intermediaries,
including renowned international institutions, for the trust
companies to choose for the appraisal and assessment, according to
the regulations.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, asset assessment will be confined to trust companies
that have gone bankrupt, or have been closed down, restructured or
merged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
