<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Convention on Bottled Water Opens in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, May 24 (Xinhua) -- More than 300 experts of the
bottled water industry from all over the world gathered at a
convention here Monday to discuss sales and marketing strategies,
market trends in Asia and new production technologies for bottled
water.
</P>
<P>
The three-day convention, sponsored by the Asia Chapter of the
International Bottled Water Association (IBWA), which was
inaugurated Monday morning, consists of an exhibition and a series
of seminars.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition features displays of advanced production
facilities and technologies, information systems, raw materials,
and packaging and labeling equipment.
</P>
<P>
Edmond Tsui, president of the IBWA Asia Chapter, said at the
opening of the meeting that people in Asia have enjoyed great
improvement in their living.
</P>
<P>
Consumers are getting more health conscious and they are urging
for better quality drinking water. Marketers thus have been
competing to supply products of higher quality standard and
greater variety to meet the increasing demand of customers, he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released by IBWA's Asia Chapter, the
total volume of bottled water consumed in Asia in 1998 was 11.93
billion liters, representing an 8 percent increase over 1997.
</P>
<P>
Thailand was the largest market, consuming a total of 4.2
billion liters.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese mainland came in second, having consumed 2.9
billion liters in 1998, representing a 21 percent increase over
the previous year. This amount was equivalent to about a quarter
of the total Asian consumption of water in the same period.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years the mainland market has experienced an
annual growth in demand for water of more than 20 percent,
demonstrating the enormous potential for future growth.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong consumed over 270 million liters of bottled water in
1998, ranking sixth in Asia. In the past few years, sales of
bottled water in Hong Kong have grown by double-digit figures
every year, surpassing the overall growth of its economy.
</P>
<P>
Despite the economic downturn, the industry still maintained
positive growth of between 6 and 7 percent, indicating growing
versatility in the local market.
</P>
<P>
Tsui said it is a top priority for the Asia Chapter to offer
guidelines and support to water industries in countries that need
to institute rules and regulations. Continuous public education
and promotion of IBWA's quality standard is equally important.
</P>
<P>
IBWA is a reputable trade association with more than 1,200
members from the bottled water industry. Its mission is to
establish stringent standards for the bottled water industry and
to assure that safe and clean bottled water is produced and
marketed to consumers.
</P>
<P>
The Asia Chapter comprises 202 members in 33 Asian countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
