<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, May 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA -- The entire Metro Manila police force is on full alert
in anticipation of massive protest actions to be staged on Monday
by militant labor groups opposing the ratification of the proposed
Visiting Forces Agreement (VFA) between the Philippines and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Star newspaper said police and military
intelligence reports showed that two groups have been preparing
for a mammoth rally in front of the Senate building. Police and
military units have been ordered to monitor closely all ongoing
activities and to take necessary and appropriate action, the
newspaper said. (Philippines-Rally)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- Newly-elected German President Johannes Rau said
Sunday that he was gravely concerned over the situation in Kosovo
and hoped that a peaceful solution could be found to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with a German television shortly after his
election, Rau, a Social Democrat, said he believed that Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder and his government ministers would make their
best efforts to push for a political solution to the crisis. He
said he was greatly worried because he could not imagine how
German soldiers who had been taught the lessons of World War II
could have gone to Yugoslavia to throw bombs. (Germany-New
President-NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesian ruling Golkar Party General Chairman
Akbar Tanjung said President B.J. Habibie did not pay serious
attention to security problems after his one-year of rule as some
cases of violence in the country remained unsolved.
</P>
<P>
In a press release issued on Sunday night, Golkar said prior to
the June 7 polls many Indonesian citizens fled the country for
fear of unrest. "This means that President Habibie could not give
a sense of security to the community," Akbar said. (Indonesia-
Security)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung Monday announced a
sweeping reshuffle of his cabinet, replacing 11 of the 17 cabinet
members.
</P>
<P>
Kang Bong-kyun, who was presidential secretary for economic
affairs, was appointed minister of finance and economy, while Lim
Dong-won, senior presidential aide for foreign affairs and
national security, was named minister for unification. Jin Nyum,
head of the Planning and Budget Commission, assumed the top post
of a newly-created body -- the Planning and Budget Agency.
Presidential Chief Secretary Kim Joong-kwon said the cabinet
shakeup this time focused on appointment of "non-politicians with
professionalism and a reform mentality." (SKorea-Cabinet-Reshuffle)
</P>
