<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Ugandan Soldiers Killed in Clash with DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- At least two soldiers of the Uganda
People's Defense Forces (UPDF) were killed over the weekend when
Ugandan army deployed in the eastern part of the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC) clashed with the rebels there.
</P>
<P>
The clash, which occurred in the northeastern city of
Kisangani, appeared to be linked to last week's split in the rebel
Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD), the Monitor paper reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The shoot-out started when opponents of ousted rebel leader
Ernest Wamba dia Wamba tried to stop a protest march in Kisangani
by his supporters.
</P>
<P>
The internal split between the top leaders of the RCD has been
deepening over the past few weeks. Last week, some founding
members of the RCD ousted Wamba and named Emile Ilunga as their
new leader.
</P>
<P>
Wamba, who is usually supported by Uganda, rejected the move
and denounced it as a coup d'etat.
</P>
<P>
Uganda Army Commander Jeje Odongo confirmed the shootings, but
declined to give any detail concerning the incident, the report
added.
</P>
<P>
Regional analysts feared that this exchange of fire might
further split the already fragmented country.
</P>
<P>
Uganda, one of the key backers of the rebels bent in toppling
DRC President Laurent Kabila, has maintained a large military
presence in the eastern part of the central African country to
allegedly protect its long border there.
</P>
<P>
There were reports that Ugandan troops had clashed with the
Rwandan soldiers, but both Kampala and Kigali denied the
allegations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
