<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Senate to Probe Marcos Account </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will leave
it to the Senate to verify reports about a 13 billion U.S. dollar
account supposedly maintained by heirs of the late president
Ferdinand Marcos abroad, a government official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said that he is willing to
cooperate with the Senate probers, even as he denied anew his
involvement in a reported plot to recover the wealth.
</P>
<P>
"I am ready to cooperate with the Senate. But I am not involved
in ongoing operations to recover the wealth," he said in a radio
interview.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, reports linked Zamora to an alleged "clandestine
operation" seeking to recover the wealth.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, Zamora tapped the services of
Presidential Anti-Organized Crime Task Force chief director
Panfilo Lacson for the "operation."
</P>
<P>
The reports stemmed from a transcript of a telephone
conversation between bounty hunter Reiner Jacobi and former
Presidential Commission on Good Government (PCGG) chairman David
Castro.
</P>
<P>
Zamora also said President Joseph Estrada ordered an immediate
verification of the reports immediately after learning of them.
</P>
<P>
"The president instructed PCGG Chairman Magdangal Elma to get
to the bottom of this, and Chairman Elma has been communicating
with the Swiss authorities," Zamora said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
