<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Say China Needs Computer Science </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- China needs to step up the
development of computer science and apply it to major projects to
tackle complicated problems, according to a group of scientists
here.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a recent symposium on large-scale computer science,
Gui Wenzhuang, director of the High-Tech Bureau of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences (CAS), said that China has developed large
computers capable of making 100 billion calculations per second.
</P>
<P>
The large-scale computers have been applied to the research on
material science, life science, cosmography, meteorology, space
and other areas, said Gui.
</P>
<P>
The increase in the computer's capacity has made it possible to
tackle very complicated problems, said Gui, adding that
computation, experiments and theoretical analysis have become
three important means in scientific research.
</P>
<P>
Sun Jiachang, a research fellow with the Software Institute of
CAS, said that the Boeing Company of the United States designs
airplanes with computers, and the simulated experiments in the
wind tunnel are also conducted by computers.
</P>
<P>
He said China should also step up the development of computer
science to shift the important research to computation.
</P>
<P>
"It's a change of the research concept and means," he said.
</P>
<P>
Yu Dehao, vice-director of the Institute of Mathematics and
Scientific Project Computer, said that theoretical analysis has
its limits in many complicated problems, and experiments are not
feasible or too costly in areas such as space science,
microphenomenon, particle disintegration and galaxy evolution.
</P>
<P>
He said that scientists have to turn to computer science to
tackle many of the complicated problems. And the development of
the computer science should aim at meeting national demand.
</P>
<P>
Gui Wenzhuang said that China should make full use of its
resources of large parallel computers and push forward the
development of other sciences.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the hardware in some Chinese institutes have met
the United States' standard of the mid-1990s, but are not fully
utilized. China should make an effort to develop efficient
computing methods in the coming five years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
