<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Bombing Victims Charge U.S. with Negligence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Some 545 Kenyan individuals and
families affected by the U.S.embassy bombing last August have
filed a complaint against the U.S. government for its abuse of
duty and negligence in rescuing Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
Phillip Musolino, an American lawyer representing the victims
of the bomb blast, last week sued the U.S. State Department in a
U.S. court for a compensation of an average of 200,000 U.S.
dollars for each victim, the East African Standard weekly reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Musolino argued in a complaint that American rescuers at the
scene of the embassy attack, which killed 213 people and injured
about 5,000 others, did not give timely assistance to wounded
Kenyans, and instead focused only on U.S. casualties.
</P>
<P>
The complaint also claimed that the U.S. failed to warn Kenyan
authorities about a suspected threat of terrorist violence.
</P>
<P>
The complaint said that before the twin bombings in Kenya's
capital Nairobi and Tanzanian capital Dar es Salaam on August 7,
the United States had received information of possible attacks on
American targets in Africa.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials were guilty of further negligence in not
securing the Nairobi embassy against a possible bombing, the
lawyer argued.
</P>
<P>
The legal action initiated by Musolino is separate from the
suits filed early this year by another lawyer John Burris, who
represents about 2,300 Kenyan victims.
</P>
<P>
U.S. government lawyers are scheduled to respond to Musolino's
motion on May 28.
</P>
<P>
Musolino said it may take three years or longer to reach a
settlement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
