<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Offers Prisons for Rwandan Genocide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambia has offered to provide prison
 facilities for convicts of the 1994 Rwanda genocide, the
International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda (ICTR) said.
</P>
<P>
Times of Zambia newspaper Monday quoted the U.N. court as
saying in a press release reaching here that it has reached an
agreement in principle with the Zambian government for this
purpose, and that the agreement is expected to be formalized
shortly.
</P>
<P>
If the agreement is signed, Zambia will become the second
country, following Mali, to accept prisoners of 1994 Rwanda
genocide in which more than 500,000 people were massacred.
</P>
<P>
On February 12 this year, the tribunal's registrar signed with
the government of Mali an agreement whereby the west African
country undertook to provide prison facilities for the enforcement
of the court's prison sentences.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the court said more African countries have expressed
 willingness to accept the Rwanda genocide prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Negotiations are at an advanced stage with the governments of
Benin and Madagascar on this issue, it added.
</P>
<P>
The ICTR, based in Arusha town in northern Tanzania, was
created by the United Nations Security Council in November 1994
after the genocide happened that year.
</P>
<P>
Several Scandinavian countries have also offered to provide
prisons for the genocide convicts, but the court preferred to let
them serve sentences in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The reason, according to Tom Kennedy, chief official of press
and public affairs of the court, is that Rwanda genocide is an
African problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
