<HEADLINE> New Zealand's Fruit Industry Heading for Record Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, May 24 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand's fruit industry is
heading for a record year, with exports likely to exceed the 1.05
billion NZ dollars (578 million U.S. dollars) earned in the year
ending June 1998.
</P>
<P>
The latest issue of New Zealand's Export News, a fortnightly
newspaper published in South Island's Christchurch, quoted Peter
Silcock, convenor of the Fruit Industry Innovation Council of New
Zealand, as saying that innovation is the "key to the industry's
continued success".
</P>
<P>
"A great deal has already been achieved. We have new fruit
varieties like the distinctively different kiwifruit Zespri Gold
which will make a big impact over the next decade. Our brands like
Enza and Zespri have won worldwide recognition," he said.
</P>
<P>
Silcock said work on identifying future directions for the
fruit industry shows there are tremendous opportunities in the
development of new fruit varieties, leveraging its intellectual
property, better techniques for growing and storing fruit and
dynamic marketing.
</P>
<P>
"We have introduced environmentally friendly growing
techniques. Then we have a company like Horticulture Automation
which has a big reputation for its state-of-the-art fruit grading
equipment and is winning export orders in many overseas
countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Silcock told the Export News that his council will, like its
predecessor (the Fruit Research Council of New Zealand), place its
focus on the research and development of the fruit industry within
the context of the wider industry and close regard to commercial
results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
