<HEADLINE> Kenyan Minister Suggests New Items in Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Tourism Minister Henry
Kosgey has advised stakeholders in the industry to explore new
opportunities like mountain climbing and bird watching in a bid
to rejuvenate the tourism sector.
</P>
<P>
Tourism, fourth biggest foreign currency earner for Kenya, has
been in a depressed situation, registering a decline since early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
If the stakeholders want to realize the target of two million
visitors by the year 2002, they can not rely solely on beach and
safari tourism, Kosgey said.
</P>
<P>
The Daily Nation newspaper Monday quoted Kosgey as saying that
it was high time for stakeholders to start marketing mountain
climbing and bird watching as tourist attractions.
</P>
<P>
If well-packaged and aggressively marketed, cruise tourism,
sports, culture and conference tours could also help the country
hit its target of two million tourists by 2002, Kosgey said
Saturday in Mombasa, the east African country's biggest port and
beach resort.
</P>
<P>
However, the minister said safari and beach tourism should not
be abandoned but rather re-packaged to make them sensitive to
environmental protection and sustainable tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
