<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt Offers Incentives to Sugar Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- In line with centerpiece agenda to
guarantee food security, the Philippine government is now taking
steps to accelerate the rehabilitation of the sugar industry, a
government news release said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada was quoted as saying that
the government is offering incentives to sugar planters and
producers so they would invest in upgrading their equipment and
facilities.
</P>
<P>
Among these incentives is a guarantee fund of 110 million pesos
(2.75 million U.S. dollars) for farmers to buy tractors, the news
release said.
</P>
<P>
It said that the problems plaguing the industry can be traced
to sugar producers and millers who are not willing to invest in
new equipment and farmers who do not use high-yielding varieties
of sugar.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Estrada unveiled a 40-billion-peso (1 billion U.S.
dollars), five-year program to modernize the sugar industry, which
he said has become a sunset industry because of government neglect
over the last several years.
</P>
<P>
The five-year plan aims to make the country self-sufficient in
sugar and restore its role as a global player in the world market.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
