<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Likely to Cut Sugar Export As Warned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, May 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa is likely to cut
its sugar export to avert an industry crisis following a warning
by the London-based International Sugar Organization (ISO), the
Star newspapers reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In its latest report, the ISO warned leading exporters to cut
sugar output by ten percent, or six million tons, to avoid a
crisis.
</P>
<P>
International sugar prices have tumbled to a 13-year low in the
past six months. The raw price of sugar fell from a monthly
average of 250 U.S. dollars a ton in October 1997 to 162 dollars
in September last year. There has been little improvement since
then.
</P>
<P>
The reduced prices represent less than half the cost of
production, and all sugar-producing nations report they are losing
money.
</P>
<P>
South Africa, among the world's top ten sugar exporters, has
also suffered from the reduced prices.
</P>
<P>
The world's major sugar exporters - Brazil, the European Union,
Thailand, Australia, Colombia, Guatemala, Mexico and South Africa
- produce an estimated 62 million tons of sugar a year.
</P>
<P>
South Africa exports about 1.3 millions tons of sugar, about
half of its production, mostly to Asia, the Middle East and
Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lhalu: An Eyewitness of Old and New Tibet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Lhalu Cewang Doje, one of the
largest serf-owners in old Tibet, said that the Tibetans have made
continuous progress in socialist construction and Tibet has won
achievements impossible in the past.
</P>
<P>
"From the progress Tibet has made I learn that only socialism
can save Tibet and Tibet can make progress only within the big
family of the motherland," said 80-year-old Lhalu, quoted by the
latest issue of "China's Tibet".
</P>
<P>
The Lhalu clan was very influential in Tibet historically as
two members of the clan were Dalai Lamas. In old Tibet, Lhalu
Cewang Doje owned a score of large and small manors and thousands
of slaves. As the high-ranking official of the local government,
he did his best, including attempt to rely on imperialist forces,
to defend the prerogative of serf-owners, and stood for "Tibetan
independence".
</P>
<P>
When Tibet achieved peaceful liberation in 1951, he was forced
by the general situation to accept the reality and was still
pondering how to maintain the interests of the three estate-
holders in power.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the Communist Party of China (CPC) and Government
leaders arranged for people from various walks of life in Tibet to
visit the hinterland. Lhalu served as delegation leader, and was
received by Chairman Mao Zedong and Premier Zhou Enlai during the
national day celebrations on October 1.
</P>
<P>
Lhalu and his delegation visited Beijing and Shanghai, where he
paid a visit to Mr. Rong Yiren, a capitalist. Upon returning home,
he made a detailed report to the Gaxag government of Tibet, which,
however, paid no heed.
</P>
<P>
In 1957, when Lhalu was appointed the granary chief, the 14th
Dalai Lama received him. Lhalu was greatly moved by the
appointment and vowed to be faithful to Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
In March 1959, reactionaries in the upper echelon of Tibetan
society rebelled and Lhalu served as commander of the rebel army.
</P>
<P>
The rebels were soon put to rout, with the 14th Dalai Lama
fleeing to India and Lhalu arrested by People's Liberation Army
troops.
</P>
<P>
"I thought I would be executed," Lhalu said. "So, I was very
stubborn in the beginning. But the government sent people to
explain policies in great detail and with great patience," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In August 1965, I was released and my gold earrings, gold
wrist watch and pen, which were taken away when I was thrown into
jail, were returned to me."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Strengthen Inspection on Fishing Boats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- China will strengthen inspection of
fishing boats in the next few years to ensure safety, according to
the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is now formulating a series of regulations and
rules to make inspection more effective.
</P>
<P>
Bao Shengqing, director of the ministry's Bureau of Fishing
Vessel Inspection, said that the small number of inspected vessels
has been a factor causing marine incidents. He said the accidents
are due primarily to the absence of a whole range of laws and
regulations, fishermen's lack of safety awareness and the
negligence of local authorities.
</P>
<P>
To implement the rules effectively, the country also plans to
improve the management and supervision of the inspection agencies
and inspectors.
</P>
<P>
The ministry promulgated a rule on fishing boat inspectors
last year and is now providing training for them.
</P>
<P>
The rule stated that by 2001, all fishing boat inspectors must
have qualification certificates.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also plans to introduce a scrapping system for
fishing vessels, said Bao, adding that the service length and the
standards for scrapping are being studied.  
</P>
</TEXT>
