<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Bigamy Laws Fail to Stop Concubines in Guangzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Judicial departments in Guangzhou
reached an agreement in April 1998 on stopping the practice of
having concubines and bigamy, which was rampant in the southern
China city adjacent to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A year later, however, no one has been prosecuted for these
crimes.
</P>
<P>
Keeping concubines or unlicensed prostitutes become acts of
bigamy and punishable according to this local law, which was
widely hailed across China and became a cover story in the media
immediately after its promulgation.
</P>
<P>
But the Guangzhou Municipal People's Procuratorate says that it
is yet to handle a such a case because the police, who are
authorized to investigate such cases, have not done their job. An
official with the Guangzhou Municipal Party Committee in charge of
law and order explains that the reason for the lack of cases is
the different understanding of the Criminal Procedure Law.
</P>
<P>
The newly revised law says that prosecutors can no longer
investigate acts of bigamy, so victims think that public
prosecutors have been deprived of the right to bring such cases to
the court and, as a result, have lost because of an inability to
find evidence.
</P>
<P>
However, police are still supposed to investigate such cases
and bring them before a prosecutor. But, due to different views of
the Criminal Procedure Law, the police has done nothing, the Party
official says.
</P>
<P>
Ding Lu, head of the Women's Rights Protection Department of
the All-China Federation of Women, says that bigamy and
concubinage have become a serious social problem and that judicial
offices across the country need to take steps to deal with this.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
