<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Han Dynasty Tomb Discovered in Xi'an </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have dug up
130 funerary items from a tomb dating back to the Han Dynasty (206
B.C.-220 A.D.) in Shangzhou in Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The tomb has a passageway and a front coffin chamber, 1.6
meters long and 3.3 meters deep. It was found recently during
construction work at the provincial power supply bureau.
</P>
<P>
The unearthed objects include over 100 coins, an iron sword
that was put on the chest of the tomb's occupants, an iron stove,
a copper basin, and some earthenware.
</P>
<P>
Judging from the burial items, the tomb's owner was a high-
ranking general at the end of the Western Han and beginning of the
Eastern Han dynasties, a turbulent period with numerous wars. The
iron stove was believed to be used for cooking while on the move.
The iron sword is well preserved.
</P>
<P>
The reason of the man's death remains a mystery.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
