<HEADLINE> Star-studded Chinese Teams for FINA Diving GP in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Swimming Association (
CSA) has entered two star-studded teams for the 1999 International
Amateur Swimming Federation (FINA) Diving Grand Prix meeting in
southeastern Chinese city of Wenzhou.
</P>
<P>
Fifteen teams from 14 countries and regions have entered for
the May 28-30 meeting, which is the eighth meeting of the 14-leg
Grand Prix series this year.
</P>
<P>
China will host two Grand Prix meetings this year, with the
other set for June 4-6 in Hong Kong, which is now a special
administrative region of China.
</P>
<P>
Among the Chinese stars are the country's former world and
Olympic champion women diver Fu Mingxia and such veteran male
divers as Sun Shuwei, Xiong Ni and Yu Zhuocheng.
</P>
<P>
At the age of 15, Fu in 1995 became the world's youngest double
gold-medalist diver, with platform wins at the Barcelona Olympics
and the 1991 world championships in Perth.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 in Atlanta, Fu became the world's youngest back-to-back
Olympic champion diver and China's first ever double gold-medalist
for both springboard and platform diving events at the same
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Fu staged a come-back last month at the national champions
diving meet, more than two years after her retirement from active
competitions. Fu, now 22, is a student of economics at Qinghua
University in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Sun had won individual platform titles at both world
championships and Olympic Games and he later became a synchronized
diving expert, winning both world championships and World Cup
titles.
</P>
<P>
Xiong became China's first ever Olympic springboard diving
champion in the 1996 Games in Atlanta and Yu is a springboard
specialist, with individual and synchronized victories from world
championships.
</P>
<P>
Among other up-and-coming Chinese divers are Wang Tianling,
Tian Liang and 15-year-old new national champions Sang Xue and
Liang Xiaoqiao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
