<HEADLINE> More Ethnic School-Age Children Get Enrollled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, May 24(Xinhua) -- Over 90 percent of school-age
children from ethnic backgrounds in China's Gansu Province are in
school.
</P>
<P>
The multi-ethnic province has 44 of the country's 55 ethnic
groups among its 2.5 million people, most of them living in
mountainous or poor areas. It is the only place in China with
Bonan, Dongxiang, and Yugur ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
To make secondary education universal in the region, state and
provincial governments allocated 18 million yuan to build 22
primary schools and renovated 65 primary and middle schools over
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
The province has also set up 126 boarding schools in pastoral
or sparsely populated areas to cater to the needs of children of
herdsmen.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1998, three autonomous counties had universal
secondary school education.  
</P>
</TEXT>
