<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest Edition Of Confucian Classic Discovered (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scholars have
identified a collection of bamboo slips unearthed in a 2,000-year-
old tomb as the earliest edition of the Confucian Analects.
</P>
<P>
The bamboo version was found in a tomb in Hebei Province, which
archeologists say belongs to an emperor of the Han Dynasty (206 BC
-- 220 AD) and dates back possibly to 55 BC.
</P>
<P>
The tomb was first discovered in the early 1990s by local
farmers who were digging water control facilities. A great number
of bamboo slips have been unearthed, but most of the characters on
them were illegible and archeologists had to use modern techniques
to reveal their true nature. Ultimately they reached the
conclusion that some of them were from the Analects, a collection
of major doctrines and sayings of the educator and philosopher
Confucius (551 -- 479 BC).
</P>
<P>
The book is more than 2,000 years old and is the earliest
edition of a Confucian work ever found, according to Xie Fei, the
director of the Hebei Cultural Relics Research Institute, who
examined the slips along with scholars from the State Cultural
Relics Bureau and Beijing's Palace Museum.
</P>
<P>
The collection consists of more than 620 bamboo slips, which
were used by the ancient Chinese before the use of paper was
popularized. They measure 16.2 centimeters by 0.7 centimeters and
contain as many as 20 characters each. There are also traces of
the silk strings that were used to connect them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 06:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fate of Some Iranian POWs Clarified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The fate of some Iranian prisoners
of war (POWs) have been clarified during recent talks between Iran
and Iraq, head of the Iranian POWs Commission Brigadier General
Abdullah Najafi announced on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Najafi said that the POWs, including 64 released by Iraq
during the past six months, had been taken captive after the
1980-1988 Iran-Iraq war, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said that delegations from the two countries held fruitful
talks on the fate of remaining POWs on November 26 and May 17.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian delegation also gained first hand information
about the fate of a number of other POWs, Najafi said, adding that
coordination would be made with the International Committee of the
Red Cross (ICRC) to decide their fate and inform their families
following completion of the investigations.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Iraqi POWs, the Iranian official said that over
the past six months, Iran released 622 Iraqi POWs under the
ICRC's supervision.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran arranged the ICRC to meet with 3,479 Iraqi
POWs on August 13, 1998 and they preferred to live in Iran and
refused to return home.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting on March 7-17, six out of 108 Iraqi POWS
interviewed by the ICRC preferred to go home and they were
delivered to Iraqi officials under the ICRC's supervision, Najafi
said.
</P>
<P>
The ICRC would continue meeting with Iraqi refugees this year
and Iran would arrange the meetings at a suitable time, he said.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Iraq exchanged 53 Iranian POWs for 450 Iraqis under an
agreement reached in March, raising the number of POWs swapped
since 1991 to 55,438 Iraqis and 39,417 Iranians.
</P>
<P>
However, Iran claimed last month that 2,806 Iranian POWs are
still held by Iraq while Iraq said there are some 2,000 Iraqis
kept by Iran. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
