the top post of a newly-created body -- the Planning and Budget
Agency.
</P>
<P>
Kim Kwang-woong, professor of Seoul National University, was
picked as the chairman of the central and personnel committee,
which is also a newly-created mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Oh Gong-geun, a former editorial writer of the Joongang Ilbo,
was made head of the new National Information Agency.
</P>
<P>
Kim Tae-joung was tapped minister for justice, former Second
Army Commander Cho Sung-tae defense minister, and Kim Duck-choong,
president of Ajou University, education minister.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Park Jie-won was appointed culture and
tourism minister and Vice Finance and Economy Minister Chung Duk-
koo became commerce, industry and energy minister.
</P>
<P>
National Tax Administration Chief Lee Kun-choon was named
construction and transportation Minster.
</P>
<P>
Cha Heung-bong, chairman of the National Pension Corp., became
health and welfare minister, Son Sook, who is co-chairman of the
Korean Federation for Environment Movement, was appointed
environment minister and former Kwangwon Province Governor Lee
Sang-yong took over the labor portfolio.
</P>
<P>
The replacement of the National Intelligence Agency Director
Lee Joong-chan will be announced late Monday and three senior
presidential secretaries and new vice ministers will be named
later, said a presidential spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Six retained cabinet members are Foreign Affairs and Trade
Minister Hong Soon-yang, Government Administration and Home
Affairs Minister Kim Ki-jae, Science and Technology Minister Suh
Jung-uk, Agriculture and Forestry Minister Kim Sung-hoon,
Information and Communications Minister Namgoong Suek and Maritime
Affairs and Fisheries Minister Chung Sang-cheon.
</P>
<P>
Presidential Chief Secretary Kim Joong-kwon said the cabinet
shakeup this time focused on appointment of "non-politicians with
professionalism and a reform mentality." 
</P>
</TEXT>
