<HEADLINE> Vietnam Launches Nation-Wide Anti-AIDS Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is to enhance its activities
against AIDS by launching an anti-AIDS month from May 25-June 30,
local press reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the nation-wide campaign is to further raise public
awareness of the danger of the deadly disease as well as the
necessity to care for HIV carriers.
</P>
<P>
The campaign focuses on the necessary measures for families and
communities to curb the spread of the epidemic as well as to care
for HIV/AIDS carriers.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam has been cited by the United Nations as a good example
in terms of strong political commitment as well as effective
prevention of the spread of HIV injection, said Chung A, vice
chairman of Vietnam's National Anti-AIDS Committee.
</P>
<P>
He said the campaign will encourage people to use condoms and
not to share hypodermic needles with anyone.
</P>
<P>
About 85 percent of HIV cases, mostly young people, have been
infected with the virus through injections.
</P>
<P>
The campaign commemorates the fourth anniversary on the
introduction of state laws to fight the deadly disease on May 31
and the International AIDS Prevention Day which falls on June 5.
</P>
<P>
Up to mid-May, more than 13,000 Vietnamese people have been
diagnosed HIV positive and more than 2,440 have contracted fully
developed AIDS and 1,292 died.
</P>
<P>
The epidemic is reportedly spreading at an alarming rate in
Vietnam's northern cities and provinces such as Quang Ninh, Hai
Phong, Lang Son and Hanoi. 
</P>
</TEXT>
