<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 20,000 Die During Child Birth Annually in Bangladesh: UNICEF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- About 20,000 women die every year in
Bangladesh due to delivery-related complications, which is one of
the highest in the world, according to a study of the United
Nations International Children's Emergency Fund (UNICEF) available
here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The main reasons behind the deaths are excessive bleeding,
obstructed labor, sepsis, abortion and eclampsia, the study
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
There are about 600,000 complicated delivery cases in the
country a year, 90 percent of which are conducted at home by
"untrained birth attendants," it said, adding that about four
million women give birth every year, 60 percent of whom are anemic
and malnourished.
</P>
<P>
The services for the management of complications are also
inadequate and under-utilized in the country, it noted.
</P>
<P>
Besides, about 30 to 50 percent of the new-born babies have low
birth weight -- less than 2.5 kilograms, and of every 1,000 babies
born alive, 12 die within hours of birth, with eight of them due
to injury during deliveries, it revealed.
</P>
<P>
Almost 75 percent of the mothers die due to delivery-related
complications and do not live to see the first birthday of their
babies, it further stated.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi government has undertaken a UNICEF-funded
special program called "Comprehensive Emergency Obstetric Care" to
avert the above-mentioned unnecessary deaths. The program will be
implemented to strengthen the capacity of health centers for safe
delivery practices in the country.
</P>
<P>
The program aims at reducing annual maternal deaths by 50
percent, increasing the number of normal deliveries attended by
trained traditional birth attendants and increasing uptake of pre-
and post-natal care services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
