<HEADLINE> Unemployment Rate Falls Steadily in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's unemployment rate has
fallen to 9.1 percent of the labor force in 1998 from 10.4 percent
the previous year, official sources said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The jobless rate fell steadily, considering the rate of 12.3
percent in 1995, 13.8 percent in 1993 and 15.9 percent in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The steady decline in unemployment in recent years reflected
the rapid economic growth and the resultant growth of employment
opportunities, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The male unemployment rate declined from 11.8 percent in 1990
to 7.1 percent last year while female unemployment fell at a
faster rate from 23.4 percent to 12.7 percent during the same
period.
</P>
<P>
Employment generation increased by about nine percent in 1998,
pushing the total number of employed persons to 6.08 million from
5.58 million in 1997, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The private sector was employing 82 percent of the total as of
last year, up from 75.6 percent in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The sources attribute the increase to the success of the
government's private-sector-led growth policy and the buoyancy of
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The favorable incentive schemes backed by prudent
macro-economic management has enabled the country to achieve an
average economic growth rate of over 5 percent during the past
five years, which is cited as another factor of helping generating
job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, 137 enterprises commenced operations under the Board
of Investment, generating 36,200 jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
