<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Gov't Decides to Build More Food Godowns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has taken
a decision to build 20 more godowns to provide further food
storage facilities in the next fiscal year starting from July
1999, The Bangladesh Observer daily newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The government will build 20 food godowns at a cost of 90
million taka (about 1.86 million U.S. dollars) from its own
sources, and the food storage capacity of these food godowns will
be 10,000 tons, each with 500-ton capacity, a Food Department
official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
At present, the government has 639 big and small food godowns
with a storage capacity of over 1.8 million tons, but the
effective storage capacity is roughly 1.5 million tons, he stated.
</P>
<P>
Of the total food godowns, 621 are local supply depots with a
storage capacity of 118,300 tons, 13 are central storage depots
with a storage capacity of 474,800 tons and the rest five are
silos with a storage capacity of 225,800 tons.
</P>
<P>
The present food grains stock position of the government is
over 1.3 million tons, which is satisfactory, he stated.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh will harvest a record 22.5 million tons of rice and
wheat in 1998-99, despite the century's worst flood that ravaged
the country last year and the severe drought this year, according
to the Ministry of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 126 million, this agriculture-based South
Asian country's annual needs of food grains is about 21 million
tons leaving a net surplus of 500,000 tons of food grains during
the current fiscal year after the earmarked one million tons as
seeds. 
</P>
</TEXT>
