<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analysts See Few Price Hikes for Building Materials in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The price of building materials in
China is not likely to pick up substantially this year although
fluctuations are possible, according to China Material News.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts say that the supply of building materials is
adequate and can meet most demand so there is no reason for prices
to go up. In the past, when supply failed to meet demand, high
prices prompted many manufacturers to expand production.
</P>
<P>
Production of major building materials like steel, cement, and
plate glass has grown a great deal since the early 1990s, leading
to an oversupply on the domestic market, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, China produced 105 million tons of steel, a 90 percent
increase from 1992, while cement production jumped 72 percent to
510 million tons, according to official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Although the present low prices of building materials will have
a negative effect on many manufacturers, large producers with low
production cost are doing a lot to expand market shares, and this
upward trend in building materials production will continue unless
prices hit a slump, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
Imports of building materials have continued to grow as well,
adding to the glut in the domestic market, the paper says,
attributing the growth to the sustained low price level on the
global market at a time when the slowdown in world economic growth
leads to an oversupply.
</P>
<P>
In addition, declining production costs of domestic building
materials enterprises have discouraged price hikes in China,
analysts say.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
