<HEADLINE> New Reservoir Put into Service in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, May 24 (Xinhua) -- One more new reservoir was put into
service in Bago township, 80 kilometers away from Myanmar's
capital of Yangon, to get drinking water, control flood and
extend cultivation in Bago division.
</P>
<P>
The Mazin Reservoir, inaugurated on Sunday, is 1,230 meters
long and 18 meters high and was built on Mazin Creek at a cost of
over 916,000 U.S. dollars, official The New Light of Myanmar
newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The reservoir is capable of supplying 50 million liters of
drinking water to the Bago township daily and irrigating 263.25
hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Bago division gets much rain in the rainy season and it faces
flood every year as it is unable to control rain water that flows
down from Bago Yoma mountain range, but there is scarcity of water
in the hot season.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Lieutenant-General Tin Oo, second secretary
of the Myanmar State Peace and Development Council, as saying that
the government relies on Bago division in production of paddy,
placing emphasis on extended cultivation of the crop.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the inauguration ceremony for the reservoir, he
expects modern farmlands to emerge soon as national entrepreneurs
are engaged in reclamation of thousands of hectares of fallow and
virgin lands in the division.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Myanmar has built 98 irrigation facilities
throughout the country in the past 10 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
