<HEADLINE> China to Build Largest Manganese Production Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous
Region in south China is expected to become the country's largest
manganese production center.
</P>
<P>
For the past several years, the central government has
allocated tens of millions of yuan for the expansion of manganese
mines in the region's Daxin County, 143 kilometers west of the
capital, Nanning.
</P>
<P>
Exploiting Daxin's 130 million tons of proven manganese
reserves started in 1960 and the county's annual mining and
dressing capacity is now 500,000 tons, according to a county
official.
</P>
<P>
To step up construction work on the center, the county has
spent 800 million yuan on transportation, energy,
telecommunications and other infrastructure facilities, as well as
related industries, in the past several years, and preferential
policies are being worked out to attract foreign investors, the
official says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientist: Rare Fish Spices Need Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, May 24 (Xinhua) -- A member of the Chinese Sturgeon
Institute says recently that the rare species of fish is in bad
need of protection.
</P>
<P>
Yi Jifang says that their numbers have decreased because of the
Gezhouba Hydro-electric Power Project on the Yangtze River which
prevents them from swimming upstream to spawn on the upper reaches.
</P>
<P>
A study of the fish before and after of the building of the
project shows that a ratio of male to female sturgeons out of
proportion over the past four years with the number of male
sturgeon dropping, but with their body length increasing and the
life expectancies of female and male sturgeon increasing by 2
years and 3.5 years respectively.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say that the hydro-electric power project has
affected the breeding patterns and that the pollution and catching
are also to be blamed for the reduced population size of the rare
fish.
</P>
<P>
Yi says, however, that a natural breeding site for the fish,
which is on the verge of extinction, has formed near Gezhouba Dam
and that their numbers can be increased through artificial
insemination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
