<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Trade News (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
trade news released by Xinhua from May 17 to 23:
</P>
<P>
 Position on WTO Entry Unchanged
</P>
<P>
China has never changed its position, viewpoint and attitude on
accession into the World Trade Organization (WTO), Shi Guangsheng,
minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation, reiterated
last Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said what China insists on is "the balance between rights
and obligations".
</P>
<P>
 China-Australia Joint Economic Commission Meeting
</P>
<P>
China and Australia will achieve more progress in bilateral
economic and trade cooperation in various forms in the near future,
Shi Guangsheng said last Monday at the 9th Session of the China-
Australia Joint Ministerial Economic Commission.
</P>
<P>
He said the two sides have made important progress in talks on
China's accession to the WTO, and he hopes they will adopt a
pragmatic spirit and constructive attitude in the following
negotiations to make further progress.
</P>
<P>
 Sino-Australian Planned Gas Project
</P>
<P>
Zeng Peiyan, minister in charge of the State Development
Planning Commission, discussed with visiting Australian Deputy
Prime Minister and Minister for Trade Tim Fischer last Monday the
planned liquefied natural gas project in south China's Guangdong
Province that the Australian side is interested in.
</P>
<P>
Zeng said that China welcomes qualified overseas investors to
bid for it.
</P>
<P>
 Overseas Investment Influx in January-April
</P>
<P>
China had approved 4,925 foreign-funded businesses by the end
of April this year, involving 11.418 billion U.S. dollars in
contracted investment. A total of 10.24 billion U.S. dollars of
overseas investment had been used during the period.
</P>
