<HEADLINE> Manila Police on Alert for Anti-Visiting Force Agreement Rallies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The entire Metro Manila police force
is on full alert in anticipation of massive protest actions to be
staged on Monday by militant labor groups opposing the
ratification of the proposed Visiting Forces Agreement (VFA)
between the Philippines and the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Star newspaper said police and military
intelligence reports showed that two groups have been preparing
for a mammoth rally in front of the Senate building.
</P>
<P>
Police and military units have been ordered to monitor closely
all ongoing activities and to take necessary and appropriate
action, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Senate security forces and police clashed with some
300 anti-VFA demonstrators who tried to storm the Senate building.
</P>
<P>
The VFA, signed by Manila and Washington last year, would pave
the way for resumption of annual large scale joint military
exercises between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Senate is due to vote on the agreement on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The opponents oppose the pact because it gives Washington
jurisdiction over U.S. troops who may commit crimes in the
country.
</P>
<P>
They say that the pact also exposes the Philippines to nuclear
threats because it does not require the U.S. to declare whether it
has weapons aboard visiting ships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
