<HEADLINE> Weekly Highlights of Trade News (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China and Australia officially launched a new Model Wool
Contract last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The contract, worked out following negations between relevant
departments of China, Australia and New Zealand over the past two
years, has been in use since March this year, according to sources
attending a China-Australia Wool Workshop.
</P>
<P>
 Logistics Workshop Held
</P>
<P>
China sponsored an International Logistics Workshop last
Tuesday, hoping to promote its logistics industry and upgrade
services in transportation, storage and distribution.
</P>
<P>
 IMF Praises China's Non-Devaluation Policy
</P>
<P>
As the Asian financial crisis has turned around the corner,
China's policy not to devalue its currency in the worst period of
the crisis has been commended as a "wise decision" by Shigemitsu
Sugisaki, deputy managing director of the International Momentary
Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
"The stable Renminbi has served well, not only for China, but
also for the world at large," he said, adding that China's non-
devaluation policy after the Asian financial crisis went full-
blown has been beneficial in a sense that "it did not trigger a
second round of exchange rate adjustments in Asia." The IMF is
pleased with China's decision.
</P>
<P>
Beijing International Fair
</P>
<P>
The biennial Beijing International Fair, one of China's largest
international trade fairs, has attracted more than 1,200
exhibitors since it opened last Thursday. On display in the 40,000-
square-meter space are machinery, transport equipment, electronics
items and computers, telecommunications equipment, light
industrial products, agricultural products, foodstuff, clothing,
silk, electric appliances, stone materials, new technology,
jewelry, and arts and crafts.  
</P>
