<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangdong's Foreign Trade Balancing Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The export volume of South
China's Guangdong Province dropped 17.8 percent in the first four
months of the year, but the fall off is slowing down month by
month.
</P>
<P>
Huang Ziqang, director of the provincial foreign economy and
trade commission, expects that the export, which stood at 19.816
billion U.S. dollars in the first four month, will balance out and
even increase in the second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
"China has overcome the impact of the Asian financial crisis
and achieved an 0.5 percent rise in export volume last year,"
Huang said, "and the province also saw a 1.6 percent increase in
its export volume during the same period."
</P>
<P>
Exports in the first month of this year were reported a 40-
percent drop compared with the same period of 1998, but the gap
shrank in the following months, with the rate of fall registering
only 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
The export volume in April reached 5.81 billion US dollars,
making a peak record this year, and only 10 percent down on last
April.
</P>
<P>
At a national trade fair hosted recently in Guangzhou, capital
of Guangdong, foreign trade volume achieved was 2.35 billion US
dollars, 27.3 percent more than the previous fair last year.
</P>
<P>
In Shenzhen, one of the country's earliest special economic
zones, the export volume reached 7.6 billion US dollars in April,
4.4 percent up on the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports in the processing trade continued to grow in the first
four months and the structure of export commodities and markets
was further improved. The share of mechanical and electrical
products in exports rose from 45 to 50.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
"To develop foreign trade and attract overseas investment, the
province is holding a major economy and technology trade fair in
Hong Kong, which usually opens in July," Huang said, adding that a
similar fair will be hosted in Japan and some European countries.
</P>
<P>
All these factors indicate that the province's foreign trade is
balancing out and forecast a brighter prospects by the end of this
year, the official noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
