<HEADLINE> Philippines Budget Gap May Soar to 2 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government may have
to revise its budget deficit target this year to 2 billion U.S.
dollars, 17 percent higher than its original target of 1.71
billion U.S. dollars, to maintain its level of expenditures and
pump prime the economy, the Manila Times newspaper said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu was quoted as saying that
since the government was able to borrow up to 1.93 billion U.S.
dollars from overseas sources to finance its budget deficit, it
can go up to 2 billion U.S. dollars only.
</P>
<P>
The government has so far raised 1.93 billion U.S. dollars from
abroad equivalent to 113 percent of the 1.71-billion-U.S. dollar
projected budget gap.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu's figure is 250 million U.S. dollars lower than the
2.25- billion-U.S. dollar deficit projected by the inter-agency
cash programming committee during its meeting on May 5, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The committee's projection was based on the assumption that
revenue collections would fall short by 516 million U.S. dollars
by yearend, the newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
