<HEADLINE> New German President Favors Peaceful Solution to Kosovo Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BERLIN, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Newly-elected German President
Johannes Rau said Sunday that he was gravely concerned over the
situation in Kosovo and hoped that a peaceful solution could be
found to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with a German television shortly after his
election, Rau, a Social Democrat, said he believed that Chancellor
Gerhard Schroeder and his government ministers would make their
best efforts to push for a political solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
He said he was greatly worried because he could not imagine how
German soldiers who had been taught the lessons of World War II
could have gone to Yugoslavia to throw bombs.
</P>
<P>
He said his major task in the next five years would be to
reduce the gap between eastern and western Germany, pledging to be
a "president for all Germans."
</P>
<P>
Rau, 68, known as the "patriarch" after 21 years of running the
state of North Rhine-Westphalia, will formally replace outgoing
President Roman Herzog on July 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
