<HEADLINE> Political Parties Urge Gov't to Continue Probe of Soeharto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian political parties Sunday
urged the government to continue the much-demanded investigation
into former president Soeharto's wealth, allegedly amounting to
around 15 billion U.S. dollars, The Indonesian Observer reported
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a campaign rally in the country's second major city
of Surabaya in East Java, ruling Golkar Party Chairman Akbar
Tanjung promised that his party would urge President B.J. Habibie
to go ahead with the corruption probe into Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
"Golkar will ask Habibie's government to follow up the People's
Consultative Assembly's (MPR's) decree on clean government, free
from corruption, collusion and nepotism (KKN) including the
examination of former president Soeharto," Akbar said.
</P>
<P>
Akbar, who resigned as minister/state secretary earlier this
month, said the probe into Soeharto should be carried out on the
basis of prevailing laws.
</P>
<P>
He said Golkar backed the move by the Attorney General's Office
to form a team to investigate a recent report by the U.S. news
magazine Time, which claimed Soeharto and his family amassed a
fortune worth an estimated 15 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The probe into Soeharto should be completed before the MPR
convenes for a general session to elect next president in August,
during which the president will present his accountability speech,
Akbar added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the United Development Party (PPP) Chairman Hamzah
Haz said it seemed that the Attorney General's Office responsible
for investigating the alleged wealth of Soeharto and his cronies
was not serious enough and could not do much.
</P>
<P>
To solve the matter, he said, there should be a reversible
probe in that Soeharto and his cronies must prove that they got
their wealth rightfully.
</P>
<P>
With the reversible probe, the Attorney General's Office must
force Soeharto and his cronies to prove that they got the wealth
not through corruption during the former strongman's 32 years of
rule.
</P>
<P>
If they could not prove that they got the wealth rightfully,
they should be sent to jail, Hamzah said at a campaign rally in
Bangil, East Java, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"As a political party channelling the people's aspirations and
proposing a trial of former president Soeharto at the MPR special
session in 1998, PPP feels that it takes a moral responsibility to
uphold the MPR decree. If PPP wins, our first step is to try
former president Soeharto," he said.
</P>
<P>
In a televised appearance last Friday, Soeharto refuted Time's
report that he greedily enriched himself and his family during his
lengthy terms in power.
</P>
<P>
The National Mandate Party leader Amien Rais Sunday dismissed
Soeharto's denial of the Time reports on his KKN practices during
his 32 year rule.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto's denial only "justifies" widespread accusations that
he was involved in decades of KKN practices with his children and
cronies, Raid said in Malang, East Java, on Sunday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
