<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hainan's Imports From Viet Nam Show Big Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, May 24 (Xinhua) -- Hainan, China's southernmost
province, imported 6.13 million U.S. dollars worth of commodities
from Viet Nam during the January-April period this year, a 249
percent rise on a yearly basis.
</P>
<P>
In the four months, the island province imported 17,967 tons of
goods from Viet Nam across the Beibu Gulf, more than double the
amount a year earlier. The imported commodities are mostly
tropical products such as coconuts, palm oil and natural rubber.
</P>
<P>
The big increase is attributed to Hainan's introduction of a
preferential policy that imposes tariffs on imports from Viet Nam
which is only half the amount charged on imported goods from other
countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
