<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, May 24 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN -- Seven people have possibly been killed in floods after
days of heavy rain over the Alpine region that covers southern
Germany, northern Austria and Switzerland, more were missing and
thousands were affected, German authorities said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Two German boot drivers were feared drowned. They had been
missing since Saturday night when their boots had been swept by
roaring rivers. (Germany-Floods)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- Sierra Leone rebels said they "were ready for the
cease-fire" starting on Monday and willing to start peace talks
with the government, a rebel official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Togo's Foreign Minister Joseph Kokou Koffigoh had met the
rebellion Revolutionary United Front (RUF) officials earlier
Sunday on the final preparation for the talks, according to radio
reports monitored here.
</P>
<P>
Sierra Leone's President Tejah Kabbah and the RUF leader Foday
Sankoh last Tuesday signed a cease-fire agreement in Lome, Togo,
to pave the road for further negotiations to end the country's
eight-year civil war. (SLeone-Peace Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. Senate will reject the use of American
ground troops to fight Serb forces, but consider backing plans for
a non-combat deployment to help Kosovo refugees return home,
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said on Sunday.  (US-Senate-
Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said Sunday that
NATO must not think in terms of an intervention by ground troops.
</P>
<P>
According to Dini, who was speaking in Catania, Sicily, the aim
must be a negotiated solution passing via the adoption of a
resolution by the UN Security Council incorporating the principles
agreed to by NATO, the EU and the Group of Eight. (Italy-NATO-
Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BERLIN -- Johannes Rau was elected the eighth post-war German
President on Sunday to succeed Germany's current President Roman
Herzog.
</P>
<P>
Rau, 68, candidate of the ruling Social Democrats, was state
premier of Germany's largest state North Rhine-Westphalia for 20
years.
</P>
<P>
He won the absolute majority of 670 required in the 1,338-seat
Federal Assembly in the second round of voting in the election. (
Germany-Presidential Election)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Airways (BA) will start flying to Tripoli in
Libya from June 3 to become one of the first major carriers to
reintroduce services there since the United Nations lifted
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The new service will be Britain's first non-stop air link with
the city, according to a Reuters report quoting BA sources.
</P>
<P>
"Tripoli has great potential as an important business market
and an emerging tourist destination, with remarkable
archaeological sites," BA's director of passenger and cargo
business Charles Gurassa was quoted as saying. (UK-Airline-Libya)
</P>
