<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast China City Promotes Reemployment for Laid-Off Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, May 24 (Xinhua) -- The port city of Dalian in northeast
China's Liaoning Province has become one of China's most
successful cities in promoting the reemployment of workers laid
off from state-owned enterprises, and guaranteeing their basic
living standards.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, Dalian has helped nearly 200,000 of
these laid-off workers find new jobs. Moreover, last July the city
established a basic living standard guarantee system covering all
local laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
About a year ago, the city government pledged that it would
provide "instant service" for those laid-off workers eager to find
a new job. According to this pledge, any laid-off workers could be
offered a new job within 48 hours after making application.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to this kind of instant service, more than 5,000
formerly laid-off workers and jobless people have found new
employers.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, all the 518 enterprises in Dalian, in
accordance with relevant policies of the central government, have
set up their own Reemployment Service Centers, which are taking
care of the basic needs of more than 50,000 local laid-off workers,
and have helped over 20,000 of them find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
Last April, the city government also decided to give subsidies
to those former laid-off workers who successfully found new jobs
but were receiving very low pay from their new employers. These
subsidies have helped raise their monthly income to some 400 to
640 yuan, greatly relieving their economic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
In the latest move by the city to help laid-off workers, the
labor departments of Dalian have opened a "computer labor
supermarket" which puts all local employment information in a
computer network, offers vocational training, and helps laid-off
workers keep up their personal files and pay their insurance fees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
