<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Team of Women Planters in Northern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, May 24 (Xinhua) -- A team of 280 women in the Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region, north China, have been doing
afforestration work for several years now.
</P>
<P>
One 38-year old mother Yang Jinhua wrote in her diary "What did
I do yesterday? Plant trees. What have I done today and what would
I like to do tomorrow? Plant more trees." She and her team have
made a contribution to the afforestration of the Greater Hinggan
Mountains by planting over 400 hectares of trees every year for
the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
When the planting season comes, they have to work hard all day,
leveling the land and digging from 5:00 in the morning to 7:00 at
night and get calluses on their hands. The most exhausting job is
carrying saplings in a 25-kilogram box for two to three kilometers.
</P>
<P>
Xie Yazhi, a 17-year-old member of the team, once fell off a
single-plank bridge into the water below. Her first reaction, she
says, was not to catch her shoes and scarf, but the saplings
because she would have had to go back to get another bunch of
saplings if those had disappeared.
</P>
<P>
The hard work has brought a lot of happiness and they always
feel excited when they see the trees they have planted growing
taller, explains another member, Yue Xiuying. Over 97 percent of
the trees they plant survive and the team is one of the best in
the region.
</P>
<P>
"Planting trees is a comparatively light forest job," Yue says,
"and besides the salary is quite good."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
