<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arrest of Pak Opposition Leader Qazi Hussain Denied </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, May 23 (Xinhua) -- A local administration of
Pakistan Sunday denied an earlier report that Qazi Hussain Ahmad,
leader of major opposition Jamaat-i-Islami (JI), had been
arrested, reported the Associated Press of Pakistan Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The District Administration of Peshawar said they forbade Qazi
from entering the de facto tribal area of Mohmand Agency but
didn't arrest him as was reported.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Commissioner Peshawar Sherzada Khan said, "Qazi was our
guest and he had a cup of tea with us in Peshawar."
</P>
<P>
Later in the evening, Qazi proceeded to Lahore by air, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The official said that District Administration Charsadda had
served a legal notice on Qazi, forbidding him from entering
Mohmand Agency.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Sunday, A JI statement said that Qazi was arrested near
Peshawar, capital of North West Frontier Province (NWFP), when he
was on his way to the tribal area in Muhammad Agency.
</P>
<P>
Qazi Hussain was proceeding to the tribal area to express
solidarity with the people who are protesting against the
government's decision to merge some parts of the agency in settled
areas, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Qazi Hussain was stopped at the entry check post of Mohammad
Agency and was not allowed to the tribal area.
</P>
<P>
The government says that no political activities are allowed in
tribal areas under the existing "Frontier Crimes Regulations."
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the News Network International, an
Islamabad-based independent news agency, a delegation from
Mohammad Agency met Qazi Hussain Saturday in Peshawar and sought
his support for their movement.
</P>
<P>
The JI chief declared his full support to the tribal people and
planned to visit the area as a sign of support, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Several people have been killed in the latest protest campaign
against the NWFP government's decision to merge several villages
of Mohammad Agency in the settled districts of Peshawar and
Charsadda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990524.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negotiated Solution on Kosovo Remains Target, Dini Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, May 23 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini
said Sunday that NATO must not think in terms of an intervention
by ground troops.
</P>
<P>
According to Dini, who was speaking in Catania, Sicily, the aim
must be a negotiated solution passing via the adoption of a
resolution by the UN Security Council incorporating the principles
agreed to by NATO, the EU and the Group of Eight.
</P>
<P>
"A political dialogue to give a solution to the Kosovo problem
must be opened up without continuing this war, without continuing
these bombardments for too long, since they hit civilians and
normal people as well as military installations," said Dini.
</P>
<P>
"I see no very rapid solution on the horizon," admitted Dini in
a later speech Sunday at a Sicilian camp for Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
"There are openings and loopholes we must use to find an agreed
solution, a negotiated political solution to give autonomy and
recognize Kosovo's identity," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also voiced about the civilian deaths in the bombing
attacks, although he said that, not being a military man, he was
in no position to judge whether they were mistakes in the sense of
being avoidable. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
